<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I"><UNDER>AMENDED</UNDER> STATEMENT OF CLAIM (Amended Notice of Action issued on January 25, 2011)</TI>
<P>1. The plaintiffs claim against the defendants:
<P1>a) damages in the sum of $6,235,719.28;</P1>
<P1>b) prejudgment interest on the sum in paragraph (a) above, pursuant to the Courts of Justice Act;</P1>
<P1>c) punitive damages in the further sum of $2,000,000.00;</P1>
<P1>d) their costs of the action;</P1>
<P1>e) such further and other relief as may seem just.</P1></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>THE PARTIES</TI>
<P>2. The plaintiff Royal &amp; SunAlliance Insurance Company of Canada (&ldquo;Royal&rdquo;) is a federal Canadian corporation which carries on business as an underwriter and issuer of among other things, property and automobile insurance, throughout Canada, with a head office located in Toronto, Ontario.</P>
<P>3. The plaintiff Canadian Northern Shield Insurance Company (&ldquo;CNS&rdquo;) is a federal corporation which carries on business as an underwriter and issuer of among other things, property and automobile insurance in British Columbia and elsewhere in Canada including Ontario, with a head office located in Vancouver, British Columbia. CNS is a<UNDER>n affiliated corporation to Royal, both of which are wholly owned subsidiaries of a common parent corporation</UNDER>.</P>
<P>4. The defendant The Co-operators Group Limited (&ldquo;Co-operators&rdquo;) is a federal Canadian corporation which carries on business as an underwriter and issuer of among other things, property and automobile insurance, throughout Canada, with a head office located in Guelph, Ontario.</P>
<P>5. The defendant 2421593 Canada Inc. (&ldquo;242-Canada&rdquo;) is a federal Canadian corporation, which prior to its change of name on September 3, 2009, was named Vancity Insurance Services Ltd. (&ldquo;Vancity&rdquo;), which carried on business as an insurance broker offering automobile and property insurance policies amongst other insurance products primarily to customers of a related corporation Vancouver City Savings Credit Union through offices of Vancouver City Savings Credit Union throughout British Columbia. The Defendant 242-Canada is a wholly owned subsidiary of Co-operators.</P>
<P>6. The defendant Federated Agencies Limited (&ldquo;Federated&rdquo;) is a Saskatchewan corporation which carries on business as an insurance broker with a place of business in Ontario located in Guelph. Federated is a wholly owned subsidiary of Cooperators, with offices in among other places, Mississauga, Ontario.</P>
<P>7. The defendant Vancouver City Savings Credit Union (&ldquo;VCU&rdquo;) is a British Columbia corporation which carries on business as a credit union in British Columbia. Vancity was at the material times a wholly owned a subsidiary of VCU.</P>
<P>8. The defendant <UNDER>7081332 Canada Ltd. (&ldquo;708-Canada&rdquo;) is a federal Canadian corporation</UNDER> which purchased Vancity effective September 1, 2009. This defendant is a wholly owned subsidiary of either Federated or Co-operators and is part of The Co-operators Group of Companies.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>THE AGREEMENT</TI>
<P>9. In or about the period beginning in late June 2008 and ending in or about the middle of July, 2008, Vancity entered into an agreement with the plaintiffs whereby Vancity accepted verbally the offer of CNS and RSA (&ldquo;the Agreement&rdquo;) submitted in March and April 2008 to Vancity at its request, being the submission of an offer in response to Van city's written Request for Interest (&ldquo;RFI&rdquo;) dated February 29, 2008 which, at Van City's request and intention, envisioned a long term &lsquo;partnership&rsquo;, in the colloquial not legal sense, with an insurance company interested &ldquo;in developing a sustainable competitive personal lines product offering&rdquo; of property insurance products (&ldquo;the Insurance Program&rdquo;) such submission of the offer in the form of a response to Van city's RFI being &ldquo;the first step to participating in a strategic long -term growth relationship with Vancity&rdquo;, as Vancity held out and represented to the plaintiffs in its RFI. Throughout, Vancity knew that while the memorialization of the Agreement was to be with CNS, Royal was an active participant, would be providing the funding for CNS to carry out the Agreement, and that Royal had national and international expertise and had the capital, technology, management and merger/rollover expertise needed to ensure that the Agreement would succeed, and throughout Vancity dealt with both plaintiffs as if they were joint contracting parties to the Agreement.</P>
<P>10. The essential terms of the Agreement were:
<P1>a) the plaintiffs would be exclusive suppliers and the Agreement would have a term of five years;</P1>
<P1>b) CNS and/or Royal would underwrite the Insurance Programs which would be marketed by Vancity during the term of the Agreement;</P1>
<P1>c) the basic commission structure for the Insurance Program payable to Vancity would be 25% on Home policies, and a sliding scale of up to 5% on Home policies depending upon the performance of that book of insurance business; Vancity was to be paid an additional 5% commission on roll over business by way of renewals from existing policies issued by other insurers.</P1></P>
<P>11. Although not a term of the Agreement, the Plaintiffs later agreed to pay a signing bonus to Vancity (the &ldquo;Bonus&rdquo;) in the amount of $135,000 and the Plaintiffs and Vancity agreed that termination of the Agreement would require two year<UNDER>s</UNDER> advance written notice.</P>
<P>12. During the foregoing late June 2008 to mid July 2008 period, Vancity represented to the plaintiffs and held out to the plaintiffs as follows:
<P1>(a) On June 28th, 2008, Vancity advised CNS that CNS had been selected as the sole carrier (exclusive &lsquo;partner&rsquo;) with Vancity under the Insurance Program.</P1>
<P1>(b) On July 3rd, 2008, Vancity met with CNS &ldquo;to ensure a common understanding of what we are committing to&rdquo; at which they discussed and agreed to further operational details such as Vancity's expectation that the plaintiffs would step in earlier than January 1st, as some or all of its existing sources of insurers would be expected to stop renewing policies or writing new policies once word got out, as it would, that CNS/Royal were Vancity's exclusive carrier;</P1>
<P1>(c) On July 3rd, 2008, a target date of January 1st 2009 was established for a public roll-out of a fully branded customized Vancity insurance product, and the plaintiffs would hire a project manager for this project;</P1>
<P1>(d) On July 4th, 2008, arrangements were made for CNS to attend branch office visits of Vancity with a representative of Vancity;</P1>
<P1>(e) On July 8th, 2008, Vancity announced to its head office and branch staff, that it had reached a major milestone in its program to establish a private label Person Lines (the Insurance Program) and that it had decided to proceed with &ldquo;a program underwritten by a single insurer and that insurer will be&rdquo; RSA [Royal]/CNS;</P1>
<P1>(f) CNS/Royal were invited and did attend Vancity's project meeting on July 10, 2008;</P1>
<P1>(g) On July 14, 2008, Vancity issued a press release announcing it &ldquo;had inked a major deal with a national insurer to underwrite an exclusive VC [Vancity] branded home insurance product&rdquo;.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>POST AGREEMENT ACTIVITIES</TI>
<P>13. Over the course of the next several months, the plaintiffs and Vancity proceeded to implement the Agreement and make it operational by:
<P1>a) Training staff;</P1>
<P1>b) Establishing computer programs and other operational and administrative procedures;</P1>
<P1>c) Hiring a project manager;</P1>
<P1>d) Underwriting and issuing insurance policies in advance of the contemplated January 1st public roll-out date of the Insurance Program in order to accommodate Vancity's need for replacement insurance for its customers whose existing policies were coming up for renewal but whose issuing insurers had become unwilling to renew in light of the public knowledge that the plaintiffs were to become the exclusive carriers for Vancity, and for insurance for new customers, all as expected and provided for as per paragraph 10(b) above;</P1>
<P1>e) Paid the paragraph 11 Bonus of $135,000 to Vancity;</P1>
<P1>f) In February 2009 worked together on providing additional claims services.</P1></P>
<P>14. The Agreement needed to be memorialized in writing and the plaintiffs worked to do this through the fall of 2008. Beginning in and following December, 2008, Vancity began dragging its feet, told the plaintiffs at the end of December that it would not cash the Bonus cheque of $135,000 it had received until the written memorialization of the Agreement was completed, and then continued to drag its feet for some months more into 2009.</P>
<P>15. Unknown to the plaintiffs, Vancity and VCU had decided at some point in the fall of 2008 that Vancity would be sold. Vancity did not disclose this to the plaintiffs but instead wished to have the plaintiffs continue with the operational and administrative work and the issuing of renewal or new policies to its customers under the Insurance Program while it was determined who would purchase Vancity. Consequently Vancity left in place the Agreement and the impression that it was proceeding with the Insurance Program, and continued to work on operational and administrative procedures such as claims services in February 2009, and the plaintiffs continued to issue insurance policies under the Agreement for the Insurance Program.</P>
<P>16. In the spring of 2009, Vancity continued to work under the Insurance Program with the plaintiffs. When the plaintiffs expressed frustration at the delay in memorializing the Agreement, Vancity replied, untruthfully, that the &ldquo;wheels of commerce are slow here ... at the present time&rdquo; when the truth, undisclosed to the plaintiffs, was that VCU and Vancity wanted to avoid memorializing the Agreement thinking, wrongly, that if nothing in writing was signed, any buyer of Vancity would be able to take the position that Vancity was not bound by the Agreement with the result that Vancity would be more attractive to a wider range of potential buyers such as other insurance companies.</P>
<P>17. In or about mid May 2009, Vancity told the plaintiffs that a purchaser had been chosen which was not the plaintiffs' bidder, and Vancity was working to finalize the terms of an agreement of purchase and sale with that purchaser but would not disclose to the Plaintiffs who the purchaser was or the business it was in, and represented falsely that it did not know what the purchaser would do with the Insurance Program, when it knew that Co-operators would or would likely become the exclusive carrier under the Insurance Program in place of the plaintiffs. Nevertheless Vancity continued to do business as usual with the plaintiffs as it had since the summer of 2008. On July 21, 2009 Vancity announced that the purchaser was Co-operators.</P>
<P>18. On September 9, 2009 Federated wrote to CNS to say that one of its subsidiaries (&ldquo;<UNDER>708-Canada</UNDER>&rdquo;) had purchased Vancity. Federated <UNDER>or 708-Canada</UNDER> had by September 1, 2009 closed the purchase of Vancity and one or both of them had control of the shares of Vancity by that point and Vancity was required to act as Federated, <UNDER>708- Canada</UNDER> and ultimately Co-operators determined. On September 9, 2009 Federated gave notice to CNS inter alia that all policies with effective dates of September 1, 2009 and later would be issued under a new broker of record The Co -operators Insurance Agencies. In determining that it would not continue to do business after September 1 2009 with the plaintiffs, Vancity breached the Agreement and was induced to do so by Federated's<UNDER>, 708- Canada's</UNDER> and Co-operators' orders that Vancity would use Cooperators as the carrier of the Insurance Program, in place of the plaintiffs.</P>
<P>19. In the alternative, Vancity and VCU conspired each with the other, in or around the fall of 2008, to misrepresent their true intentions and to mislead the plaintiffs into believing that the Agreement was going to be memorialized in writing so that they could enjoy the benefits of the plaintiffs' continuing to perform the Agreement and, among other things, continuing to issue insurance policies on existing customers' renewals or for new customers, thus maintaining and expanding Vancity's customer base which would attract a higher price from a prospective purchaser. In furtherance of the conspiracy, each did the following overt acts:
<P1>(a) VCU directed Vancity to take the actions set out below;</P1>
<P1>(b) Vancity represented that it was business as usual under the Insurance Program and conducted itself accordingly to give and maintain that false impression;</P1>
<P1>(c) Vancity continued to deal with the plaintiffs in the same way it had since the summer of 2008;</P1>
<P1>(d) Vancity worked with the plaintiffs to further refine claims handling procedures in early 2009;</P1>
<P1>(e) Vancity misrepresented to the plaintiffs that the reason the memorialization of the Agreement was proceeding as slowly as it had been, was that the &lsquo;the wheels of commerce are slow here&rsquo;, when the true reason was that Vancity and VCU were stalling to keep what they, mistakenly, believed would keep their options open to attract other insurers to purchase Vancity and enhance the purchase price available, by not having a written memorialization of the Agreement in place.</P1></P>
<P>20. In or around the spring of 2009, Federated, Co-Operators, and <UNDER>708-Canada</UNDER> (collectively &ldquo;the Co-operators Group&rdquo;) joined the above conspiracy and conspired with and amongst each member of the Co-operators Group as well as Vancity and VCU. The objects of this conspiracy now were to continue to maintain the foregoing pleaded illusions of normal business under the Insurance Program and continue to misrepresent the true intentions of the conspirators, by maintaining the false illusion that it would be business as usual and that Vancity would continue to perform under the Agreement, so that the conspirators could maintain Vancity's customer base until the closing of the sale of Vancity to the Co-operators Group which was successfully completed on or about September 1, 2009. In furtherance of this conspiracy, Vancity, VCU, and the Co-operators Group performed the following overt acts:
<P1>(a) VCU and the Co-operators Group directed Vancity to take the actions set out below;</P1>
<P1>(b) Vancity continued to act as pleaded in paragraphs 19(b) and (c) above.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>DAMAGES</TI>
