<BLOCK1><TI>STATEMENT OF DEFENCE OF 2421593 CANADA INC. AND VANCOUVER CITY SAVINGS CREDIT UNION</TI>
<P>1. The Defendants 2421593 Canada Inc. (formerly Vancity Insurance Services Ltd.) (&ldquo;VISL&rdquo;) and Vancouver City Savings Credit Union (&ldquo;Vancity&rdquo;) (together, the &ldquo;Vancity Defendants&rdquo;) admit none of the allegations contained in the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>2. The Vancity Defendants deny the allegations contained in paragraphs 1, 5, 7 and 9&ndash;23 of the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>3. The Vancity Defendants have no or insufficient knowledge concerning the allegations contained in paragraphs 2&ndash;4, 6 and 8 of the Statement of Claim.</P>
<P>4. Vancity is a credit union governed by the <EM>Credit Union Incorporation Act</EM>, R.S.B.C. 1996, c. 82. Until September 1, 2009, VISL was a wholly owned subsidiary of Vancity in the business of insurance brokerage.</P>
<BLOCK2><TI>The Relationship Between VISL and CNS/RSA</TI>
<P>5. In or about October 1998, VISL and the Plaintiff Canadian Northern Shield Insurance Company (&ldquo;CNS&rdquo;) entered into an agreement entitled &ldquo;Broker Agreement&rdquo;, by which VISL agreed to offer insurance policies underwritten by CNS to VISL's clients on a non-exclusive basis.</P>
<P>6. In or about August 2004, VISL and the Plaintiff Royal &amp; SunAlliance Insurance Company of Canada (&ldquo;RSA&rdquo;) entered into an agreement entitled &ldquo;Broker Agreement&rdquo; by which VISL agreed to offer insurance policies underwritten by RSA to VISL's clients on a non-exclusive basis.</P>
<P>7. In or about January 2008, CNS became a wholly owned subsidiary of RSA, following which CNS and RSA often acted jointly in their dealings with VISL.</P>
<P>8. In or about March 2008, VISL sent a document (the &ldquo;RFI&rdquo;) entitled &ldquo;Request for Interest&rdquo; to CNS, inviting CNS to express its interest in entering into a business alliance respecting VISL's &ldquo;personal lines&rdquo; portfolio (an &ldquo;Alliance&rdquo;). VISL sent a similar document to other insurers, several of which (the &ldquo;Other Insurers&rdquo;) responded with expressions of interest.</P>
<P>9. Also in or about March 2008, CNS and RSA responded to the RFI, requesting &ldquo;investigative due diligence and discussion&rdquo;. CNS and RSA proposed that the parties &ldquo;jointly sign a non-binding Letter of Intent that will allow [the parties] to enter exclusive detailed negotiations ..., the outcome of which will be a full legal contract with a 5-year tenure&rdquo;.</P>
<P>10. In or about [May 2008], VISL sent a document (the &ldquo;Guidelines&rdquo;) entitled &ldquo;Proof of Concept Guidelines&rdquo; to CNS and RSA. VISL sent a similar document to the Other Insurers.</P>
<P>11. The Guidelines stated that VISL required additional information and did not at that time intend to make any agreement regarding an Alliance:
<QUOTE><P>The intent of this next stage is not to finalize or reach definitive agreement on these items but rather to achieve a fuller understanding of the requirements, work effort, workflow, timeline, and partnership expectations if the parties were to proceed with the proposed program.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>12. In or about June 2008, CNS and RSA sent a document (the &ldquo;Discussion Paper&rdquo;) entitled &ldquo;Discussion Paper&rdquo; to VISL, by which CNS and RSA outlined some potential aspects of an Alliance. The Discussion Paper confirmed that the parties had not made any agreement regarding an Alliance and that the essential terms of any agreement in that regard, including as to commissions and termination, remained to be negotiated.</P>
<P>13. Subsequently, VISL decided to focus its attention on entering into an Alliance with CNS and RSA, to the exclusion of the Other Insurers, and began meeting with CNS and RSA to negotiate the terms an agreement in that regard and to discuss how an Alliance might be implemented.</P>
<P>14. Pending the making of an agreement regarding an Alliance, VISL continued to offer insurance policies underwritten by CNS and RSA to VISL's clients. VISL also continued to offer insurance policies underwritten by other insurers to VISL's clients.</P>
<P>15. On December 1, 2008, CNS sent VISL a draft agreement between VISL and CNS regarding an Alliance (the &ldquo;Draft Alliance Agreement&rdquo;), under cover of a letter from CNS describing it as &ldquo;the first draft&rdquo;. The Draft Alliance Agreement
<P1>(a) contained drafting &ldquo;bullets&rdquo; to indicate missing text;</P1>
<P1>(b) omitted several of its Schedules; and</P1>
<P1>(c) included the heading &ldquo;Draft for Discussion Purposes&rdquo;.</P1></P>
<P>16. In or about February 2009, Vancity offered its shareholding in VISL for sale to various insurers, including RSA. RSA, and thus CNS, knew or ought to have known that Vancity's shareholding in VISL, if not purchased by RSA, could be purchased by a competing insurer, in which case VISL would likely not make an agreement regarding an Alliance.</P>
<P>17. By no later than May 25, 2009, RSA, and thus CNS, learned that Vancity had indeed agreed to sell its shareholding in VISL to a third party, which Vancity later publicly announced to be the Defendant The Co-operators Group Limited (&ldquo;Co-operators&rdquo;).</P>
<P>18. On September 1, 2009, through its wholly owned subsidiary, 7081332 Canada Ltd., Co-operators acquired Vancity's shareholding in VISL, following which VISL ceased to procure insurance services from CNS and RSA.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>No Breach of Contract, Bad Faith, Misrepresentation or Conspiracy</TI>
<P>19. VISL never made the &ldquo;Agreement&rdquo;, as defined in the Statement of Claim, or any other agreement forming an Alliance with CNS or RSA.</P>
<P>20. At all material times, VISL negotiated with CNS and RSA in good faith and in a commercially reasonably manner, and did not engage in any misrepresentation.</P>
<P>21. The Vancity Defendants specifically deny having entered into any conspiracy with each other or other of the Defendants, as alleged in the Statement of Claim or at all</P>
<P>22. The Vancity Defendants specifically deny having engaged in any high-handed or reprehensible conduct, as alleged in the Statement of Claim or at all.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>No Damages</TI>
<P>23. The Vancity Defendants deny that CNS and RSA have suffered any of the damages alleged in the Statement of Claim and put CNS and RSA to the strict proof thereof. If CNS and RSA have suffered any of the damages alleged, which is not admitted but specifically denied, such damages were caused by no act or omission for which the Vancity Defendants are legally responsible.</P>
<P>24. Additionally, the damages alleged in the Statement of Claim are excessive, duplicative and remote and CNS and RSA have failed to mitigate them.</P>
<P>25. The Vancity Defendants therefore request that this action be dismissed against them with costs.</P>
