<BLOCK0><TI>FACTUM OF VANCOUVER CITY SAVINGS CREDIT UNION AND 2421593 CANADA INC.</TI>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. This is a case about business people getting ahead of themselves. In their excitement over a proposed business venture, they lost sight of the need to agree on clear and definite contract terms. In the end, no contract was signed, clear and definite terms were never agreed orally, and one of the parties decided to go in a different direction. The (spumed) counterparty now claims that there was a legally enforceable contract as of a date early in the parties' discussions&mdash;even though the parties continued to negotiate for months, and continued to disagree on material terms including compensation. Despite the lack of any written agreement and the months-long discussions about the terms of the proposed arrangement, is the spumed counterparty correct that a legally enforceable contract was formed?</P>
<P>2. Vancouver City Savings Credit Union (&ldquo;<BOLD>Vancity</BOLD>&rdquo;) is a Vancouver-based financial institution. Until September 2009, it owned Vancity Insurance Services Ltd. (&ldquo;<BOLD>Vancity Insurance</BOLD>&rdquo;),<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Vancity Insurance is now known as 2421593 Canada Inc.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> which was an insurance broker offering auto and property insurance policies primarily to Vancity customers.</P>
<P>3. In 2008, Vancity Insurance engaged in discussions with Canadian Northern Shield Insurance Company and Royal &amp; SunAlliance Insurance Company of Canada (&ldquo;<BOLD>CNS and RSA</BOLD>&rdquo;) towards an arrangement whereby CNS and RSA would become the sole supplier of insurance products to Vancity Insurance. Discussions proceeded for several months, but eventually ended when Vancity decided to sell Vancity Insurance to The Co-Operators Group Limited, Federated Agencies Limited and 7081332 Canada Ltd. (collectively, &ldquo;<BOLD>Co-Operators</BOLD>&rdquo;).</P>
<P>4. The main issue in this case is whether the arrangement between Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA proceeded to the point of a legally enforceable contract.</P>
<P>5. There is no dispute that no written contract was ever signed: a first draft was circulated in December 2008, but matters never proceeded to the point of a final draft much less an executed agreement. There is also no dispute that there were protracted discussions between the parties, and that a considerable amount of operational work was done by the parties to enable CNS and RSA to become the sole supplier to Vancity Insurance. Where the parties differ is on the question of whether a legally enforceable contract arose on the basis of the parties' oral discussions.</P>
<P>6. Specifically, CNS and RSA point to one specific meeting, held on July 3, 2008, as the point at which they claim a legally enforceable contract arose. Does careful scrutiny of the July 3, 2008 meeting support the contention that a legally enforceable contract was formed on that date?</P>
<P>7. It does not. The parties continued their contract discussions for months thereafter, with a major contract meeting on September 11, 2008 and a draft contract provided on December 1, 2008. This reality in itself is a strong indication that a legally enforceable contract did not arise on July 3, 2008. Moreover, significant elements of a very complex proposed commercial arrangement remained unsettled as of July 3, 2008, including such crucial matters as the compensation to be paid under the arrangement.</P>
<P>8. The law is clear that a legally enforceable contract does not arise: (i) where, viewed objectively, essential terms have not been agreed but instead have been left by the parties for future agreement; (ii) where, viewed objectively, the provisions of what has been agreed are insufficiently certain; and (iii) where, viewed objectively, the parties intend that a preliminary agreement is not to create binding contractual relations until a subsequent formal document is executed. Looking at the matter from an objective perspective and not a retrospective subjective viewpoint (in other words, the perspective that is mandated by law), all three of these circumstances are present.</P>
<P>9. In addition to the main contract claim, CNS and RSA assert an alternative claim that there was a conspiracy between Vancity/Vancity Insurance and Co-Operators. This claim can be easily dismissed. There is no evidence whatsoever of a conspiracy. Vancity and Co-Operators engaged in a <EM>bona fide</EM>, arm's length commercial transaction by which Vancity Insurance was sold by Vancity to Co-Operators. It was a straightforward commercial transaction, not a conspiracy.</P>
<P>10. Summary judgment ought therefore to be granted dismissing the action.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;THE FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI>Early discussions: February 29, 2008 to June 26, 2008</TI>
<P>11. On February 29, 2008, Vancity Insurance issued a request for interest (the &ldquo;<BOLD>RFI</BOLD>&rdquo;) asking a number of insurers to express their interest in developing an exclusive supplier arrangement with Vancity Insurance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Request for Interest; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2B, pp. 10&ndash;24.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> CNS and RSA responded to the RFI, through a document dated March 2008 and entitled &ldquo;Building the Vancity Insurance Customer Proposition&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Building the Vancity Insurance Customer Proposition; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2B, pp. 25&ndash;47.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>12. Following the submission by CNS and RSA of the &ldquo;Building the Vancity Insurance Customer Proposition&rdquo; document, there were some initial conversations between Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA. These were very conceptual, high-level discussions that took place over coffee. At this stage, there was no discussion about contract terms, the length of the arrangement, or compensation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Examination for discovery of Tony Hayes (&ldquo;<BOLD>Hayes Discovery</BOLD>&rdquo;), Q90-Q91; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2B, p. 52.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There is no dispute that there was no legally enforceable contract at this stage.</P>
<P>13. Importantly, the &ldquo;Building the Vancity Insurance Customer Proposition&rdquo; document set out the manner in which the proposed transaction would be undertaken: the parties would first enter into a non-binding letter of intent, followed by approximately six weeks of exclusive detailed negotiations, followed at that point by a &ldquo;full legal contract&rdquo; with a five year term.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Building the Vancity Insurance Customer Proposition; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2B, p. 44; Hayes Discovery, Q93&ndash;Q98; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2B, pp. 52&ndash;54.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>14. From the outset, it was apparent to both parties that the proposed arrangement was complex and unique. As Tony Hayes, a representative of CNS and RSA, testified at his examination for discovery: &ldquo;this was quite different from any other deal we had ever done before&rdquo; because &ldquo;[i]t was large. It was multi-insurer portfolio rollover. And it was non-traditional. So it wasn't a traditional broker/insurer relationship. It was more of a partnership to build a product for them. So it wasn't&mdash;it wasn't typical.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q99 to Q102; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2B, pp. 54-55.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. On June 10, 2008, Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA had a meeting at which CNS and RSA presented a proof of concept document entitled &ldquo;Beyond the RFI ... Experiencing Partnership&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Confidential Discussion Paper, &ldquo;Beyond the RFI ... Experiencing Partnership&rdquo;; Motion Vancity, Tab 2C, pp. 56&ndash;123.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Up to this stage, discussion of contract terms was limited,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q152&ndash;Q157; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2C, pp. 126&ndash;128.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> there was no agreement on commission rates to be paid to CNS and RSA,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q158&ndash;Q166; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2C, pp. 128&ndash;130.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and there was no agreement on the business and operating model.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q167&ndash;Q169; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2C, p. 130.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. On June 26, 2008, Glen Pentland of Vancity Insurance informed Ken Keenan of CNS and RSA that they had been &ldquo;selected to enter exclusive negotiations to become their sole insurer&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email dated June 26, 2008 from Ken Keenan to others at CNS and RSA; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2D, p. 131.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There is no dispute between the parties that &ldquo;at this point there is no deal in place, this is just the start of exclusive negotiations towards a deal&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q172; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2D, p. 133.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The July 3, 2008 meeting</TI>
<P>17. A key meeting was held on July 3, 2008. At Mr. Hayes' examination for discovery on behalf of CNS and RSA on March 25, 2014, CNS and RSA were unable to identify the point at which they believed a legally enforceable contract had been formed with Vancity Insurance and took the question under advisement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q606; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2P, p. 277.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> A year later, when CNS and RSA served their affidavits in response to this summary judgment motion, they identified the July 3, 2008 meeting as the point at which they now claim a legally enforceable contract was formed. Accordingly, it is important to scrutinize carefully exactly what was agreed at the July 3, 2008 meeting, the certainty of what was agreed, what was left for future determination, and whether as at July 3, 2008 a further formal contract document was contemplated.</P>
<P>18. The parties left the July 3, 2008 meeting with &ldquo;many action items&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Glen Pentland (Vancity Insurance) dated July 4, 2008; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2F, p. 151.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> These action items included the following:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Meeting Minutes; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2E, pp. 134-135.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<P1>(a) &ldquo;Need to secure a confidentiality agreement (Karen to provide Glen with a sample)&rdquo;.</P1>
<P1>(b) &ldquo;RSA/CNS to provide boiler plate contract for review/discussion&rdquo;.</P1>
<P1>(c) &ldquo;Branded RSA product with Pure Home&mdash;possibly September 1&rdquo;.</P1>
<P1>(d) &ldquo;Fully branded customized product with Pure home&mdash;January 1&rdquo;.</P1>
<P1>(e) &ldquo;Scott to approach Keith for availability to come to BC next week to develop new business strategy and processes. This will include evaluation of RSA/CNS's current competitiveness, identifying gaps (and pricing dislocation) and accommodation options to facilitate new business to RSA/CNS.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(f) &ldquo;Will need process in place to immediately identify any challenges with accepting new business and resolution procedures.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(g) &ldquo;Beckie to scope timing, requirements and Bravado availability for the roll-over process.&rdquo;</P1>
<P1>(h) &ldquo;Karen to explore Inventure's (Vancity IT Group) availability for rollover support and portfolio transfer analysts&rdquo;.</P1>
<P1>(i) &ldquo;RSA/CNS will hire a project manager for this project.&rdquo;</P1></P>
<P>19. At this point, commission rates had not yet been set, and many operational issues remained to be worked out.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q188-Q189; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2E, p. 141.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. From this point onwards, discussions between Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA proceeded on two parallel tracks: (i) a contract track, which was designed to address contract terms and move to a written agreement; and (ii) an operational track, which addressed moving over existing business to CNS and RSA, dealing with gaps in product and price, and developing the new product that would be marketed jointly by Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA (which would be known as Vancity BOB).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q217&ndash;Q219; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2E, pp. 149-150.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. After the July 3, 2008 meeting, there were no material discussions on contract terms until a further meeting on September 11, 2008.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q265; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2G, p. 155.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The September 11, 2008 contract meeting</TI>
<P>22. On the contract track, Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA had a meeting on September 11, 2008 to discuss contract terms. In light of the claim CNS and RSA now assert that a legally enforceable contract was already in place as of July 3, 2008, it is interesting to ask why the parties were bothering to have a meeting to contract terms, and to consider what was actually discussed at the September 11, 2008 contract meeting and what the open issues still were both going into and coming out of that meeting.</P>
<P>23. Prior to the September 11, 2008 contract meeting, CNS and RSA had an internal discussion to discuss their negotiating position with Vancity Insurance in the upcoming discussions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q276; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2H, p. 159.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Again, one should query why a negotiating position was needed if, as CNS and RSA now contend, a legally enforceable contract had been in place since July 3, 2008. Those internal discussions within CNS and RSA &ldquo;were around exclusivity, they were around all of the things that we've kind of discussed, the five-year term, the two-year cancellation. We talked about SLA, or Service Level Agreements, for both claims and underwriting. Those are all things that are not in a standard contract.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q272; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2H, p. 158.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> At this point, the SLAs had not been agreed with Vancity Insurance.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q275; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2H, p. 159.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>24. Vancity Insurance prepared a document dated September 8, 2008 setting out the issues to be discussed at the September 11, 2008 meeting (the &ldquo;<BOLD>September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document</BOLD>&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2I, p. 160.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document was provided to CNS and RSA in advance of the meeting, and is very telling in terms of the contention that CNS and RSA now advance that a legally enforceable contract was already in place.</P>
<P>25. Contrary to the claim that CNS and RSA now advance that a legally enforceable contract was already in place, the September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document begins with a plan to enter into a non-binding letter of intent:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><N>1.</N><TI>&lsquo;Spirit and Intent&rsquo; Partnership Agreement</TI>
<P>Develop a one to two page document that summarizes the &lsquo;spirit and intent&rsquo; of the partnership and is signed by Ken and Terry. <BOLD><EM>This is a non-legal document that will summarize the vision, spirit and intent of the partnership</EM>.</BOLD>
<ITEM><P>Identify the vision, values, goals and expectations of the partnership.</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Identify how the partnership will move beyond the traditional supplier-broker relationship</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Identify the triple-bottom line commitment and opportunities to drive community leadership through the partnership</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Commit to have joint performance targets (KPIs) and joint strategies to achieve the targets</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Confirm willingness of insurer to obtain financial services from Vancity&rdquo; [Emphasis added.]</P></ITEM></P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P>
<P>26. The September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document then addresses the need for a &ldquo;Three Year Strategic Plan&rdquo; and the need to &ldquo;identify&rdquo; a number of parameters of the arrangement between the parties:
<QUOTE><P><ITEM><P><BOLD><EM>Identify</EM></BOLD> three year and annual growth targets and KPIs</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><BOLD><EM>Identify</EM></BOLD> strategies to achieve these targets</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><BOLD><EM>Identify</EM></BOLD> strategies for community leadership [Emphasis added.]</P></ITEM></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>27. Representing the unique nature of the proposed arrangement, the September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document makes it clear that the contract that was under contemplation was bespoke and not something off-the-shelf: &ldquo;Start with an existing insurer/broker contract and identify contractual requirements that differ from the standard Company-Broker Agreement (RSA may have examples of other agreements to work from)&rdquo;.</P>
<P>28. The September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document makes clear that an agreement was required in respect of certain technology costs:
<QUOTE><P><ITEM><P>Who pays for changing technology requirements</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Who pays for IT transitional costs over year one, two and three.</P></ITEM></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>29. The September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document contemplated a nondisclosure/confidentiality agreement and a privacy agreement, but did not set out any terms for either one:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><TI>Confidentiality/Privacy</TI>
<P><ITEM><P>Non-disclosure confidentiality agreements included as addendum to contract</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>Privacy agreement.</P></ITEM></P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P>
<P>30. The September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document noted the need for a &ldquo;[c]laims process for Vancity&rdquo;, the need to &ldquo;<BOLD><EM>identify</EM></BOLD> auditing procedures, responsibilities, timing, reporting&rdquo; [emphasis added], the need to &ldquo;<BOLD><EM>identify</EM></BOLD> mechanisms for remuneration assessment&rdquo; [emphasis added].</P>
<P>31. In stark contrast to the claim that CNS and RSA now assert that there was a legally enforceable contract in place already, the September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document makes it clear that commission rates were not yet settled and contemplates further negotiations on the point:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><TI>Profit-sharing</TI>
<P><ITEM><P>Increase from current 1-2% to <BOLD><EM>up to</EM></BOLD> 5% (<BOLD><EM>CNS proposal</EM></BOLD>)</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P>CPC% increase from 10% to 25% (<BOLD><EM>CNS proof of concept</EM></BOLD>)</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><BOLD><EM>Need to identify creative ways to structure commission and profit sharing</EM></BOLD> to support growth and underwriting objectives. [Emphasis added.]</P></ITEM></P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P>
<P>32. The September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document made it quite clear that much work remained to be done on SLAs:
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><N>4.</N><TI>Service Level Agreement (SLA)</TI>
<P><BOLD><EM>Identify</EM></BOLD> key service level agreement terms and performance standards. This <BOLD><EM>could be</EM></BOLD> an addendum to the contract or a separate agreement that is updated as required.
<ITEM><P><BOLD><EM>Identify</EM></BOLD> working relationship expectations and summarize day-to-day involvement</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><BOLD><EM>Identify</EM></BOLD> the problem resolution process and the specific staff involved at each level</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><BOLD><EM>Identify</EM></BOLD> partnership opportunities to create innovative community and/or environmental benefits; this should include incorporating similar benefits into the program product design.</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><BOLD><EM>Identify</EM></BOLD> how to define rate competitiveness and include in SLA.</P></ITEM>
<ITEM><P><BOLD><EM>Identify</EM></BOLD> roles + responsibilities for web tools, including ongoing maintenance. [Emphasis added.]</P></ITEM></P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P>
<P>33. With respect to these various items, Mr. Hayes confirmed the following on his examination for discovery:
<P1>(a) It was in fact contemplated in September 2008 that there would be a one-to two-page non-binding spirit and intent document.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q280; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2I, p. 163.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> No such document was ever actually drafted, much less signed.</P1>
<P1>(b) As of September 2008 there was no agreement on three year and annual growth targets and KPIs. Indeed, at no point was there ever agreement on these points.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q283-Q284; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2I, p. 164.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(c) As of September 2008 there were no technology service agreements in place. Indeed, they were never put in place.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q304-Q305; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2I, p. 169.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(d) As of September 2008 there was no agreement in place with respect to who would pay IT transitional costs in the second and third years of the relationship.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q309-Q310; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2I, p. 170.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(e) Mr. Hayes did not know if there had been agreement that confidentiality agreements would be included as an addendum to the contract.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q312; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2I, pp. 170-171.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(f) As of September 2008 a claims promise for Vancity Insurance had not been agreed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q315; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2I, p. 171.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(g) As of September 2008 there had been no agreement on who would pay for marketing support.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q438; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2I, p. 178.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(h) As of September 2008 there had been no agreement on key performance measurement criteria, or on the consequences of non-performance, or key service level agreement terms, or performance standards.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q369-Q370 and Q373-q374; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2I, pp. 182&ndash;184.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1>
<P1>(i) As of September 2008 the details of the termination provisions had not been agreed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q410; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2I, pp. 186-187.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>34. The minutes of the September 11, 2008 contract meeting confirm the inconclusive nature of the arrangements at the time, and add another point of uncertainty: &ldquo;need to agree on rollout dates&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Minutes of September 11, 2008 meeting; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2J, p. 188.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Mr. Hayes confirmed on discovery that as of September 2008 there had not yet even been agreement on when the new Vancity BOB product would be rolled out.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q413; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2J, pp. 190-191.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The December 1, 2008 &ldquo;solid first draft&rdquo; contract</TI>
<P>35. The contract discussions next advanced on December 1, 2008, when CNS and RSA forwarded to Vancity Insurance a &ldquo;first draft of the Vancity/CNS contract&rdquo;, noting that they hoped it would &ldquo;serve as a solid first draft for us to work on.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>December 1, 2008 letter from Tony Hayes (CNS and RSA) to Terry Taciuk (Vancity Insurance); Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2L, p. 204.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>36. The &ldquo;solid first draft&rdquo; was accompanied by a letter that set out the views of CNS and RSA on what compensation should be: &ldquo;With regard to compensation, I thought it best that we outline how we see the various levels of compensation under the new partnership agreement.&rdquo; It further provided that transaction commissions on new business would rise to 23% and then further to 25%, but at some unknown future date: &ldquo;Once we have a fully formed Vancity proposition in 2009, we will of course set a date to move to the 25% commission levels as per the original proposal.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><BOLD><EM>Ibid.</EM></BOLD></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>37. Mr. Hayes confirmed on discovery that the December 1, 2008 draft contract &ldquo;wasn't a document [he] expected Vancity just to sign, [he] expected this to be a solid first draft to work on with Vancity.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q534; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2L, p,. 253.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>38. While Mr. Hayes asserted on discovery that some of the compensation points he referred to in his covering letter were agreed, he admitted that not all were: &ldquo;Parts of it are already in play, parts are not.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q537; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2L, p. 254.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>39. Mr. Hayes confirmed on discovery that a number of the provisions in the draft December 1, 2008 contract had not been agreed with Vancity Insurance. Schedule C provided for several matters that had not been agreed with Vancity Insurance, and Schedule D was entirely blank.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q550&ndash;Q563; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2L, pp. 257&ndash;260.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Schedule E contemplated a commission schedule that had not been agreed, and Schedule G had an incomplete chart on service levels because there had not yet been agreement on those service levels.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q564&ndash;Q567; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2L, pp. 260-261.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>40. The reaction of Glen Pentland of Vancity Insurance to the draft December 1, 2008 contract was &ldquo;I think it is close&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Glen Pentland (Vancity Insurance) to Tony Hayes (CNS and RSA) dated December 11, 2008 at 4:52 p.m.; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2M, p. 262.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> On discovery, Mr. Hayes acknowledged that he understood at the time that this meant that &ldquo;there were still open issues to be discussed&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Discovery, Q574-Q575; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2M, p. 266.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>41. Mr. Hayes followed up on the draft December 1, 2008 contract by asking whether the parties were &ldquo;on the same page&rdquo; with respect to compensation rates:
<QUOTE><P>Have you had a chance to look at the memo outlining compensation? <BOLD><EM>Just want to make sure that we are all on the same page to avoid any confusion</EM>.</BOLD></P>
<P>The memo outlines the payments as being seperated [<EM>sic</EM>] by rollover bonus of 5%, new business commission at 23% but does not anticipate moving the rollover business until renewal into the full program product next year.</P>
<P><BOLD><EM>Does this fit with your understanding as well</EM>?</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Tony Hayes (CNS and RSA) to Glen Pentland (Vancity Insurance) dated December 11, 2008 at 11:27 a.m.; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2M, p. 262.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [Emphasis added.]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>42. Mr. Pentland's response to this query revealed that the parties were not in fact &ldquo;on the same page&rdquo;: &ldquo;Somewhere I had understood it would be 25% for new business beginning December 1 as CNS would be our sole supplier at the time for new business.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Glen Pentland (Vancity Insurance) to Tony Hayes (CNS and RSA) dated December 11, 2008 at 4:52 p.m.; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2M, p. 262.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Further confusion about compensation rates</TI>
<P>43. Further email exchanges in January 2009&mdash;allegedly four months after a legally enforceable contract was in place (according to the position now asserted by CNS and RSA)&mdash;reveal that there was considerable confusion and disagreement about compensation levels. On January 6, 2009, Mr. Pentland of Vancity Insurance wrote to Mr. Hayes of CNS and RSA to acknowledge that &ldquo;[t]here may have been some misunderstanding on the amounts for payments&rdquo; and stated that &ldquo;I need to be sure we are all agreed&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Glen Pentland (Vancity Insurance) to Tony Hayes (CNS and RSA) dated January 3:57 p.m.; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2N, p. 267.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In response, Mr. Hayes did not agree with Mr. Pentland's understanding but instead said, &ldquo;I think its [<EM>sic</EM>] a good idea if we sit down and make sure we are all on the same page and crystal clear to avoid confusion. ... I don't think we are far off the mark but there are a few things we need to discuss as we move from 20% up to an enhanced commission.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Tony Hayes (CNS and RSA) to Glen Pentland (Vancity Insurance) dated January 7, 2009 at 8:26 p.m.; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2N, p. 267.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>44. The parties then met to discuss the point, which was followed by an email in which Vancity Insurance set out what it understood the compensation model to be: &ldquo;As discussed, we see the compensation model during this phase as follows.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Email from Tony Hayes (CNS and RSA) to Glen Pentland (Vancity Insurance) dated January 9, 2009 at 4:17 p.m.; Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2O, p. 273.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The contract is never signed</TI>
<P>45. The &ldquo;solid first draft&rdquo; never proceeded any further. No contract was ever signed. In the spring of 2009, Vancity decided to sell Vancity Insurance to The Co-operators, and discussions between Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA ceased. After the sale closed in September 2009, this lawsuit followed.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The response of CNS and RSA to this motion</TI>
<P>46. Mr. Hayes was examined for discovery on March 25, 2014. Two months later, on June 23, 2014, Vancity and Vancity Insurance served this motion for summary judgment. CNS and RSA then took nearly a year to serve their responding materials, and came up with three affidavits&mdash;by Mr. Hayes sworn June 10, 2015, by Glen Pentland sworn June 17, 2015, and by Keith Mottram sworn June 18, 2015.</P>
<P>47. All three of the responding affidavits were clearly very carefully crafted&mdash;no doubt by CNS and RSA's counsel over the full year that they took to come up with them&mdash;to attempt to paint a picture very different than that painted by the documents and by Mr. Hayes' examination for discovery, specifically that of a fully concluded deal. Given how long it took for CNS and RSA to create the three responding affidavits and how different a picture they paint than the documentary evidence and the discovery evidence of Mr. Hayes in March 2014, the three responding affidavits should be scrutinized carefully. They do not withstand careful scrutiny, and ought to be rejected.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The evidence of Keith Mottram</TI>
<P>48. The easiest one to deal with is the evidence of Mr. Mottram. Mr. Mottram worked for CNS and RSA and had responsibility for managing the transfer, or &ldquo;rollover&rdquo;, of insurance business from Vancity Insurance's other insurers to CNS and RSA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Affidavit of Keith Mottram (&ldquo;<BOLD>Mottram Affidavit</BOLD>&rdquo;), para. 1; Responding Motion Record of CNS and RSA, Vol. IV, Tab C.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The punch line of Mr. Mottram's evidence is that he believed there was a full commitment between Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA, and that there was nothing contingent about the arrangement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See Mottram Affidavit, para. 27; Responding Motion Record of CNS and RSA, Vol. IV, Tab C.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> But the cross-examination of Mr. Mottram revealed that this belief has no probative value because of Mr. Mottram's role.</P>
<P>49. On cross-examination, Mr. Mottram admitted that he had no involvement in the response of CNS and RSA to the RFI, and in fact was not even aware that the response document was being created at the time it was prepared.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Cross-examination of Keith Mottram (&ldquo;<BOLD>Mottram Cross-Examination</BOLD>&rdquo;), Q38-Q39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Similarly, he was not involved in the meeting between Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA to discuss the proposal document of CNS and RSA, and was not even aware at the time of the existence of either the document or the meeting.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mottram Cross-Examination, Q46&ndash;Q48.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He was not among the large group of individuals at CNS and RSA who were informed on June 26, 2008 that CNS and RSA had been selected by Vancity Insurance to enter into exclusive negotiations.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mottram Cross-Examination, Q49&ndash;Q53.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>50. Mr. Mottram accepted the characterization of Mr. Hayes on his discovery that after the July 3, 2008 meeting there were two tracks of discussions between Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA, namely a contract track and an operational track. Crucially, he admitted that <BOLD><EM>all of his work was on the operational track, and that he was not even aware at that time that the contract track existed</EM></BOLD>:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mottram Cross-Examination, Q59&ndash;63.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>Q. Okay. And you will agree with me that, put in these terms, that put your work on the operational track, as Mr. Hayes put it?</P>
<P>A. That would be correct, yes. It was certainly an operational activity.</P>
<P>Q. Right. And on the contract track, the other track, dealing with the contract terms of Vancity, that was not the track that you were involved with? You were on the operational track?</P>
<P>A. <BOLD><EM>I wasn't involved in the contract at all</EM>.</BOLD></P>
<P>Q. Right. And <BOLD><EM>were you even aware that there were these contract discussions going on on the side at the same time</EM>?</BOLD></P>
<P>A. <BOLD><EM>No</EM>.</BOLD> [Emphasis added.]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>51. Every single one of the meetings Mr. Mottram lists in his affidavit were on the operational track, with no discussion of the contract at any of the meetings Mr. Mottram attended.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mottram Cross-Examination, Q80.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>52. The reality that the contract track and the operational track operated entirely independently of one another&mdash;with Mr. Mottram having no involvement in the contract track and no knowledge of anything that was taking place on it&mdash;is best illustrated by the fact that on September 11, 2008 there were meetings on both tracks, specifically the September 11, 2008 contract meeting described above, and a separate operational meeting/call in which Mr. Mottram participated. Mr. Mottram did not even know that a contract meeting was taking place on the same day as his operational meeting.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Mottram Cross-Examination, Q84&ndash;Q91.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>53. Accordingly, Mr. Mottram's beliefs are easily discounted. He had no visibility whatsoever into the contracting process. He was tasked with an operational exercise that sheds no light on whether there was sufficient certainty of agreement on essential terms. Mr. Mottram's evidence is irrelevant to the issue that is before the court.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The evidence of Glen Pentland</TI>
<P>54. Next it becomes necessary to consider the evidence of Mr. Pentland. At the time of the events in question Mr. Pentland was employed by Vancity Insurance. Upon the sale of Vancity Insurance, he became an employee of Co-Operators. While Mr. Pentland's affidavit attempts to portray certainty of terms as between Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA, his cross-examination revealed a very different picture.</P>
<P>55. On cross-examination, Mr. Pentland agreed that coming out of the July 3, 2008 meeting&mdash;the meeting at which CNS and RSA now claim that a legally enforceable contract was formed&mdash;&ldquo;there were many action items that needed to be worked on as the partnership, as you put it, was put in place&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Cross-examination of Glen Pentland (&ldquo;<BOLD>Pentland Cross-Examination</BOLD>&rdquo;), page 8, lines 5&ndash;10.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Included among the issues that needed to be resolved were a confidentiality agreement (which was important to Vancity because of privacy concerns) and considerable operational work.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Pentland Cross-Examination, page 8, line 19 to page 9, line 19; page 10, line 14 to page 11, line 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>56. Mr. Pentland admitted that at the time of the September 11, 2008 contract discussions, Vancity Insurance was contemplating a one- or two-page non-binding document that would guide the discussions towards the final contract.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Pentland Cross-Examination, page 19, line 18 to page 21, line 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Going into the September 11, 2008 meeting &ldquo;there was nothing yet in writing agreed by both sides as to what the vision, values, goal and expectations of the partnership would be&rdquo;: &ldquo;there were some agreements that were made and some agreements still outstanding. But the need to get it onto paper.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Pentland Cross-Examination, page 22, line 12 to page 23, line 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Included among the items that Mr. Pentland wanted this document&mdash;which did not yet exist&mdash;to include were: (i) a commitment to joint performance targets, or KPIs; (ii) the specific KPIs; (iii) the consequences in terms of compensation flowing from the KPIs; and (iv) specific growth targets over the first three years of the arrangement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Pentland Cross-Examination, page 23, line 9 to page 24, line 14 and page 26, lines 5&ndash;9.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>57. Aside from the letter of intent document, Mr. Pentland admitted that a formal contract would have to be specifically negotiated: &ldquo;[t]here was no agreement just off the shelf that would fit this unique arrangement&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Pentland Cross-Examination, page 28, lines 12&ndash;16.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>58. Mr. Pentland admitted on cross-examination that going into the September 11, 2008 meeting, Vancity Insurance wanted a two-year notice period for termination of the arrangement. That point had been discussed but not yet agreed:
<QUOTE><P>Q. But that was still an open issue that needed to be confirmed or agreed at the September 11, 2008 meeting?</P>
<P>A. I think we&mdash;I mean, in my view we had fairly strong assurances from Ken Keenan directly in terms of where we were going. Was it written down? No. Was it clearly two years? No.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Penland Cross-Examination, page 28, line 23 to page 29, line 8 and page 30, lines 5&ndash;11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>59. Other open items going into the September 11, 2008 meeting were who would pay for IT transitional costs; auditing procedures, responsibilities, timing and reporting; profit sharing for growth; a contingency plan and disaster response in case of a major disaster in the lower mainland of B.C.; and service level terms and performance standards.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Pentland Cross-Examination, page 31, lines 7&ndash;16; page 32, line 20 to page 33, line 6; page 34, line 16 to page 35, line 10; page 35, line15 to page 36, line 8; and page 36, lines 9&ndash;22.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>60. When carefully scrutinized, Mr. Pentland's evidence does not support the contention that a legally enforceable contract was formed on July 3, 2008. Too many essential terms remained outstanding as at September 11, 2008, much less at July 3, 2008.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The evidence of Mr. Hayes</TI>
<P>61. The evidence of Mr. Hayes in response to this motion attempts to do a remarkable thing, namely resile from the clear picture portrayed by the documents and by Mr. Hayes' own prior examination for discovery evidence. The primary technique used by Mr. Hayes in this effort is to discount his prior evidence and the documents&mdash;even documents he himself created&mdash;as simply &ldquo;wrong&rdquo;.</P>
<P>62. On cross-examination, Mr. Hayes frankly admitted that going into the July 3, 2008 contract discussion meeting, it was &ldquo;open season&rdquo; with everything having to be negotiated:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Cross-examination of Tony Hayes (&ldquo;Hayes Cross-Examination&rdquo;), page 7 line 17 to page 8, line 8.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>Q. But at this point there were issues that needed to be discussed with Vancity.</P>
<P>A. Absolutely.</P>
<P>Q. There were lots of issues that needed to be discussed with Vancity.</P>
<P>A. Absolutely.</P>
<P>Q. Including how you were going to do this operationally?</P>
<P>A. Correct.</P>
<P>Q. Including commission levels.</P>
<P>A. Correct.</P>
<P>Q. Including basically everything?</P>
<P>A. Correct.</P>
<P>Q. And <BOLD><EM>so going into the first discussions, which were on July 3<SUP>rd</SUP>, 2008, it was open season. Everything needed to be negotiated</EM>.</BOLD></P>
<P>A. <BOLD><EM>Correct</EM>.</BOLD> [Emphasis added.]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>63. Mr . Hayes seeks to discount the reference in the documentation surrounding the September 11, 2008 contract discussions to Vancity Insurance wanting a two-year notice period for termination by claiming there was a prior agreement on July 3, 2008 to a one-year notice period, which was changed on September 11, 2008. The difficulty with this theory is that it is entirely unsupported by the documentation, which contains no hint either of an agreement to a one-year notice period or to an amendment to change the notice period to two years.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Cross-Examination, page 33, line 4 to page 34, line 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>64. Mr. Hayes' document summarizing the issues to be discussed at the September 11, 2008 contract meeting makes no reference to any agreement to increase the commission rate to 23 percent, as Mr. Hayes now claims had already been agreed. He dismisses the lack of documentary evidence of any agreement to a 23 percent commission rate as an &ldquo;error&rdquo; and &ldquo;oversight&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Cross-Examination, page45, line 19 to page 46, line 23.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In his affidavit he had said &ldquo;I did not set out the agreement to pay 23 percent on an interim basis as that would not form part of the written contract.&rdquo; When confronted by that statement on cross-examination, he said &ldquo;I'm not sure what I meant by that&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Cross-Examination, page 46, lines 13&ndash;17.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>&mdash;a sure sign that the words of paragraph 61 came from counsel and not the witness. Mr. Hayes then admitted that commission rates would have to be included in a written agreement, but dismissed his own document as an &ldquo;oversight&rdquo;:
<QUOTE><P>Q. Okay. So you see it as an error not to refer to the 23 percent in your summary document?</P>
<P>A. Yes. Commission would be included in a contract and should have been included in this document. It was just simply an oversight.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>65. Mr. Hayes also discounted his reference to an LOI as an error. He claimed that by September 11, 2008 a letter of intent was no longer necessary, but he had no explanation for his own reference at around that time to an LOI (&ldquo;The LOI would specify service agreements but rather point to the future development of an acceptable SLA&rdquo;) other than to say it was an &ldquo;error&rdquo;: &ldquo;I'm saying that any reference to an LOI was an error. That was the wrong term to use.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Cross-Examination, page 49, line 18 to page 50, line 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He also sought to dismiss a second reference he made to an LOI as another &ldquo;error&rdquo;:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Cross-Examination, page 57, lines 1&ndash;12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>Q. So when you say you probably should have, you&mdash;you now think that it was an error that you included it in there?</P>
<P>A. I do. We were&mdash;there was no call for a document, whether you call it a spirit and intent or LOI. We were completely in the midst of the program.</P>
<P>Q. Okay. So you say you made a mistake in referring to that in item 1 and you made a mistake in referring to an LOI at the end of item 4, Have I&mdash;</P>
<P>A. Correct.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>66. By December 1, 2008, Mr. Hayes claims that there was an agreement to move from an interim 23 percent commission rate to a rate of 25 percent, but only reluctantly admitted on cross-examination that there was never any agreement on the date on which the commission rate would increase, and that the date would require a mutual agreement of Vancity Insurance, CNS and RSA.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Cross-Examination, page 65, line 9 to page 67, line 14.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> He later admitted, again reluctantly, that the parties never actually agreed on the date on which the commission rate would increase:
<QUOTE><P>Q. Right. And there never was in fact an agreement on moving to full program, to the 25?</P>
<P>A. Oh, yes.</P>
<P>Q. No, no, no. You never agreed on a specific date when it would move to 25?</P>
<P>A. No. We just agreed that it would move to 25.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>67. No credence should be placed in Mr. Hayes's revised evidence as demonstrated by his responding affidavit. That evidence simply cannot be reconciled with the documentary evidence&mdash;including documents Mr. Hayes himself wrote at the time&mdash;or with Mr. Hayes' unscripted discovery evidence, at which he candidly acknowledged the many issues that were never agreed between the parties. Mr. Hayes' attempts to explain away contradictions between his revised testimony and the documents as multiple &ldquo;errors&rdquo; simply defies belief. The truth is revealed by the documents and by what Mr. Hayes candidly said on discovery. It is not revealed by the responding affidavit that took a year to craft and clearly represents a revisionist view of history.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The conspiracy allegations</TI>
<P>68. No doubt recognizing the weakness in its claim that a legally enforceable contract was formed, CNS and RSA also allege a conspiracy. On Mr. Hayes' discovery they were unable to offer any evidence in support of the alleged conspiracy. None of the affidavits filed in response to this motion offer any evidence either. The conspiracy allegations are clearly unsupported by any evidence and are clearly without merit.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ISSUES</TI>
<P>69. Was a legally enforceable contract formed on July 3, 2008, as CNS and RSA now allege?</P>
<P>70. Is there any basis for the allegations of a conspiracy?</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;THE LAW AND ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><TI>Preliminary point: there is no impediment to summary judgment</TI>
<P>71. This case fits well within the parameters for summary judgment set out by the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>:
<QUOTE><P>There will be no genuine issue requiring a trial when the judge is able to reach a fair and just determination on the merits on a motion for summary judgment. This will be the case when the process (1) allows the judge to make the necessary findings of fact, (2) allows the judge to apply the law to the facts, and (3) is a proportionate, more expeditious and less expensive means to achieve a just result.</P>
<P>These principles are interconnected and all speak to whether summary judgment will provide a fair and just adjudication. When a summary judgment motion allows the judge to find the necessary facts and resolve the dispute, proceeding to trial would generally not be proportionate, timely or cost effective. Similarly, a process that does not give a judge confidence in her conclusions can never be the proportionate way to resolve a dispute. It bears reiterating that the standard for fairness is not whether the procedure is as exhaustive as a trial, but whether it gives the judge confidence that she can find the necessary facts and apply the relevant legal principles so as to resolve the dispute.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak v. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC 7</CITE><PARANUM>49-50</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>72. Much of the evidence in this case is documentary, and to the extent that findings of fact are necessary they can be made on the basis of the documentary record and the extensive examination for discovery and cross-examinations. The only aspect of the case approaching a credibility issue is Mr. Hayes' about-face between his discovery evidence and his affidavit sworn in response to this motion, but the inconsistencies in his evidence can be resolved by the evidence given on the cross-examination on his affidavit. Moreover, it would be perverse and contrary to principles of proportionality to conclude on the basis of contradictions in the evidence of CNS and RSA's own witness that there is a genuine issue requiring a trial.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The contract issue: the proper approach to the issue</TI>
<P>73. The question of whether a legally enforceable contract has been formed must be determined objectively. The subjective intentions and beliefs of Mr. Hayes, Mr. Pentland and Mr. Mottram are not relevant, and indeed are inadmissible:
<QUOTE><P>A determination as to whether a concluded agreement exists does not depend on an inquiry into the actual state of mind of one of the parties or on the parole evidence of one party's subjective intention. See <CASEREF><SOC>Lindsey v. Heron &amp; Co.</SOC><CITE>[1921] O.J. No. 75</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>64 D.L.R. 92</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>S.C. (App. Div.)</COURTJUR></CASEREF>.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Olivieri v. Sherman</SOC><CITE>2007 ONCA 491</CITE><PARANUM>44</PARANUM></CASEREF>. See also <CASEREF><SOC>Apotex Inc. v. Allergan, Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 FCA 155</CITE><PARANUM>44&ndash;51</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>74. It is trite law that &ldquo;a court will not attempt to enforce what is effectively an &lsquo;agreement to agree&rsquo; or a list of guiding principles to be negotiated into specific rights and obligations&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Berthin v. Berthin</SOC><CITE>2016 BCCA 104</CITE><PARANUM>48</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>75. The proper approach to determining whether there is a legally enforceable contract was set out by Cromwell J.A. (as he then was) in <CASEREF><SOC>United Gulf Developments Ltd. v. Iskandar</SOC></CASEREF>:<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><CITE>2008 NSCA 71</CITE><PARANUM>82</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>
<QUOTE><P>The judge sought, as he should, to determine from the perspective of an objective, reasonable bystander, in light of all the material facts, whether the parties intended to contract and whether the essential terms of that contract could be determined with a reasonable degree of certainty: see G.H.L. Fridman, <EM>The Law of Contract in Canada</EM>, 5th ed. (Toronto: Thomson Carswell, 2006) at p. 15. While evidence of one party's subjective intent has no independent place in this interpretative exercise, it has long been settled that whether the legal effect of a document is conditional on future agreements must be decided having regard, not only to the terms of the document, but to the &lsquo;genesis and aims of the transaction.&rsquo;: <CASEREF><SOC>Hillas &amp; Co., Ltd. v. Arcos, Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1932] All E.R. Rep. 494</CITE><COURTJUR>H.L.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> per Lord Wright at 502; <CASEREF><SOC>Canada Square Corp. v. Services Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1982</YEAR><CITE>1981 CanLII 1893</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>34 O.R. (2d) 250</CITE><PAGENUM>at 258</PAGENUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>.</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The contract issue: the legal framework</TI>
<P>76. The leading authority in Ontario (and indeed in Canada) on what constitutes a legally enforceable contract is the Ontario Court of Appeal's decision in <CASEREF><SOC>Bawitko Investments Ltd. v. Kernels Popcorn Ltd.</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><YEAR>1991</YEAR><CITE>79 D.L.R. (4th) 97</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> (&ldquo;<BOLD><EM>Bawitko</EM></BOLD>&rdquo;).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> <EM>Bawitko</EM> establishes that there are three circumstances in which an agreement does not constitute an enforceable contract: (i) there is no enforceable contract where essential terms have not been agreed but instead have been left by the parties for future agreement; (ii) there is no enforceable contract where the provisions of what has been agreed are insufficiently certain; and (iii) there is no enforceable contract where the parties intend that a preliminary agreement is not to create binding contractual relations until a subsequent formal document is executed. As expressed by <EM>Bawitko</EM>:
<QUOTE><P>However, when the original contract is incomplete because essential provisions intended to govern the contractual relationship have not been settled or agreed upon; or the contract is too general or uncertain to be valid in itself and is dependent on the making of a formal contract; or the understanding or intention of the parties, even if there is no uncertainty as to the terms of their agreement, is that their legal obligations are to be deferred until a formal contract has been approved and executed, the original or preliminary agreement cannot constitute an enforceable contract. In other words, in such circumstances the &lsquo;contract to make a contract&rsquo; is not a contract at all. The execution of the contemplated formal document is not intended only as a solemn record or memorial of an already complete and binding contract but is essential to the formation of the contract itself.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM> at para. 21.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>All three of these circumstances are present in this case.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Essential terms were not agreed but instead were left by the parties for future agreement</TI>
<P>77. As of the conclusion of the July 3, 2008 meeting, a large number of matters remained to be determined, including commission rates, operational issues, confidentiality terms, SLAs, and termination provisions.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See paragraphs 18-19 <EM>supra</EM>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> These missing elements are not &ldquo;technical or administrative matters&rdquo; but rather are &ldquo;necessary components of the overall ... undertaking&rdquo;, resulting in the obligations being assumed by the parties being &ldquo;unclear and uncertain&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Consulate Ventures Inc. v. Amico Contracting &amp; Engineering (1992) Inc.</SOC><CITE>2007 ONCA 324</CITE><PARANUM>87</PARANUM><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>leave to appeal refused</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>2007 CanLII 45678</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>. Specifically, the alleged agreement at issue in that case lacked provisions for the nature of a land development, the respective responsibilities of the parties in respect of that development, and how encumbrances were to be dealt with.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>78. The absence of agreement on commission rates is, in itself, fatal. Price is invariably an essential element of a legally enforceable contract.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>L.C.D.H. Audio Visual Ltd. v. I.S.T.S. Verbatim Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1988</YEAR><CITE>40 B.L.R. 128</CITE><COURTJUR>Ont. H.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> and <CASEREF><SOC>EdperBrascan Corp. v. 117373 Canada Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>2000</YEAR><CITE>50 O.R. (3d) 425</CITE><COURTJUR>S.C.J.</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>affd.</CASEDISP><CASEREF><YEAR>2002</YEAR><CITE>23 B.L.R. (3d) 42</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>79. Not only were commission rates not settled on July 3, 2008, there was confusion between the parties right up to January 2009 as to what the commission rates were,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See paragraphs 43-44.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> and there was clearly never an agreement on the date on which the commission on new business would rise to 25%.</P>
<P>80. Like <EM>Bawitko</EM>, the missing elements as of July 3, 2008 go far beyond &ldquo;mere formalities or routine language&rdquo; in a complex arrangement that mandated &ldquo;express agreement on the detailed provisions set up to regulate the business relationship of the parties&rdquo;:
<QUOTE><P>In <BOLD><EM>my view, the terms of the franchise beyond those agreed to cannot be regarded as mere formalities or routine language</EM>.</BOLD> This is not a conventional document that requires only the filling in of blank spaces or the completion of minor details which the parties can impliedly be taken to have agreed upon. The terms of the draft clearly include material conditions essential to this kind of specialized contract. The very nature of the franchisor-franchisee relationship mandates that there be <BOLD><EM>express agreement on the detailed provisions set up to regulate the business relationship of the parties</EM>.</BOLD> Here, taking the respondent's evidence at its highest, there was no meeting of the minds necessary for a completed contract. Certain terms, as the trial judge found, were agreed to on April 18, but others essential to the proposed contractual arrangement, with respect to which he made no findings, remained open for negotiation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Bawitko</EM>, <EM>supra</EM> footnote 74 at para. 26.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> [Emphasis added.]</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>81. The situation was no different after the September 11, 2008 contract meeting. No doubt the parties were somewhat closer to agreement, but significant elements&mdash;including compensation and termination provisions&mdash;remained uncertain and to be agreed.</P>
<P>82. Indeed, the mere fact that material contract terms were the subject of negotiations at the contract meeting on September 11, 2008 contradicts the suggestion that a legally enforceable contract was formed at the meeting on July 3, 2008.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>See <CASEREF><SOC>Nova Growth Corp. v. Kepinski</SOC><CITE>2014 ONSC 2763</CITE><PARANUM>150</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>83. Like <EM>Bawitko</EM>, the December 1, 2008 &ldquo;solid first draft&rdquo; contract was not a conventional document requiring the filling in of blank spaces or the completion of minor details. Certain terms had been agreed, but others that were essential remained open for negotiation.</P>
<P>84. In <CASEREF><SOC>United Gulf Developments Ltd. v. Iskandar</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Supra, footnote 73.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> a written document was found not to constitute a legally enforceable contract where it &ldquo;was not a simple agreement of purchase and sale&rdquo; but rather an agreement which &ldquo;mapped out how the parties would proceed on a cooperative basis with a substantial residential development.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><EM>Ibid.</EM> at para. 2.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The document failed to specify how six blocks of land would be serviced, how the six blocks would be allocated, and how road frontage for one of the blocks would be achieved. Similarly in this case, the alleged agreement relates to a substantial, long-term exclusive supply arrangement, with no agreement on a number of essential elements.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The provisions of what had been agreed were insufficiently certain</TI>
<P>85. For similar reasons, what the parties did manage to agree on at the July 3, 2008 meeting was not sufficiently certain to constitute a legally binding contract. Nor did the narrowing of issues at the September 11, 2008 contract meeting achieve sufficient certainty.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>The parties did not intend to create binding contractual relations until a subsequent formal document was signed</TI>
<P>86. The entire structure of the transaction, starting from the &ldquo;Building the Vancity Insurance Customer Proposition&rdquo; document in March 2008 right through to the September 8, 2008 Contract Negotiations Document contemplated that there would be a non-binding letter of intent followed by a period of negotiation followed then, and only then, by a legally enforceable contract. At the relevant time, there is no evidence that anyone thought that a legally binding arrangement would be put in place prior to execution of a formal agreement&mdash;which never happened. The December 1, 2008 covering letter that accompanied the &ldquo;solid first draft&rdquo; of the contract shows no sign that CNS and RSA (the creators of the covering letter) thought that a legally enforceable contract was already in place.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>December 1, 2008 letter from Tony Hayes (CNS and RSA) to Terry Taciuk (Vancity Insurance); Motion Record of Vancity, Tab 2L, p. 204.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Instead, the covering letter, viewed objectively, is part of a continuing negotiation process that would not culminate until a formal document was signed.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>There is no evidence of a conspiracy</TI>
<P>87. The conspiracy allegations are patently without merit.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Conclusion</TI>
<P>88. There is no doubt that in the summer and fall of 2008, CNS and RSA were excited about the prospect of becoming Vancity Insurance's exclusive supplier, and plunged headlong into a significant amount of work to achieve that goal. But they got ahead of themselves, and close scrutiny of the parties' interactions reveals that they never managed to agree on all essential terms, or with sufficient certainty, and that they never got to the stage of a final written agreement which was always intended to be the point at which legally enforceable relations would arise. Disappointed with the way things turned out, CNS and RSA now look at the past with revisionist lenses, and subjectively see a comprehensive agreement which never actually arose at the relevant time.</P>
<P>89. No legally enforceable contract ever arose. There was no conspiracy. None of the allegations raise a genuine issue requiring a trial. This long-outstanding action (commenced in 2010) is amenable to summary judgment, and ought to be dismissed on that basis.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>90. Vancity and Vancity Insurance therefore request an order dismissing this action with costs.</P>
<P><BOLD>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED</BOLD> this 5<SUP>th</SUP> day of July, 2016.</P>
