<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The Co-operators Group Limited (&ldquo;Co-operators&rdquo;) is a holding company with subsidiaries which carry on business in the financial services sector, including insurance. It was the successful bidder in an auction by Vancouver City Savings Credit Union (&ldquo;VCU&rdquo;) of its shares in its wholly owned subsidiary, VanCity Insurance Services Ltd. (&ldquo;VISL&rdquo;), an insurance brokerage. The Plaintiffs (&ldquo;RSA/CNS&rdquo;) were unsuccessful bidders in that auction process.</P>
<P>2. There is no dispute that the auction process was fair and that Co-operators was at arm's length from VCU. As a result of its successful bid, Co-operators entered a Share Purchase Agreement dated July 21, 2009 with VCU (&ldquo;the SPA&rdquo;). 7081332 Canada Ltd. (&ldquo;708 Canada&rdquo;) is a subsidiary of Co-operators which was incorporated to purchase the shares of VISL.</P>
<P>3. Federated Agencies Limited (&ldquo;Federated&rdquo;) is also a subsidiary of Co-operators which carries on business as an insurance broker. However, Federated is not a party to the Share Purchase Agreement and the basis on which it was joined as a Defendant is unclear. Cooperators, Federated and 708 Canada are referred to by the plaintiffs in their Amended Statement of Claim, without differentiation, as Co-operators. In this Factum, they are referred to collectively as &ldquo;the Co-operators Group&rdquo;.</P>
<P>4. It is common ground that the Co-operators Group had no involvement whatsoever in the negotiations and meetings which are alleged to have taken place between VISL and RSA/CNS in 2008-2009 regarding the proposal for an exclusive underwriting relationship between them. When Co-operators was invited to bid on the shares of VISL in February 2009, it had no knowledge of the dealings between those parties. It is admitted by RSA/CNS that there was no relevant contact between RSA/CNS and Co-operators, Federated or 708 Canada at any time prior to Co-operators entering the SPA.</P>
<P>5. As detailed below, when Co-operators became aware of the negotiations between RSA/CNS and VISL during the course of its due diligence, it was advised by the management of VCU that there was no binding agreement with RSA/CNS with regard to the program which had been under negotiation. Co-operators necessarily relied on the representations of VCU in that regard.</P>
<P>6. The causes of action against the Co-operators Group are set out, somewhat opaquely, in paragraphs 18 and 20 of the Amended Statement of Claim. Paragraph 18 appears to allege that Federated, 708 Canada and Co-operators ordered YISL to use Co-operators as the carrier of its insurance program in place of the plaintiffs and thereby induced VISL to breach the alleged agreement it had with RSA/CNS. Quite apart from the fact that none of Co-operators, Federated and 708 Canada is an insurance company and, therefore, could not have acted as the carrier of the insurance program, there is absolutely no evidence of any such order having been given to VISL. The uncontradicted evidence is to the contrary.</P>
<P>7. Similarly, there is no evidence that the Co-operators Group had any knowledge that there was a binding agreement between the plaintiffs and VISL, or that any of the Co-operators Group intended to cause VISL to breach any agreement. Indeed, to the extent that there was a binding exclusivity agreement between RSA/CNS and VISL, as alleged by the plaintiffs, that agreement was effectively breached when VCU decided to sell VISL and invited Co-operators, RSA/CNS and other insurance companies to bid on the purchase of its VISL shares. As the successful bidder responding to VCU's invitation to bid, Co-operators cannot be said to have induced VISL to breach any agreement it might have had with RSA/CNS. In short, the evidence is wholly inadequate to support a cause of action for the tort of inducing breach of contract.</P>
<P>8. The plaintiffs plead in the alternative that in the Spring of 2009, Co-operators, 708 Canada and Federated joined an existing conspiracy between VISL and VCU with the object of convincing the plaintiffs of the &ldquo;illusion that it would be business as usual&rdquo; so that VISL's customer base could be maintained until the closing of the sale of VISL. There is simply no evidence of any such conspiracy.</P>
<P>9. Obviously, if VCU's position that there is no binding agreement with RSA/CNS is accepted, there would not be any basis for a claim against the Co-operators Group for the tort of inducing breach of contract. Similarly, as the only unlawful conduct identified by the plaintiffs as the basis for their conspiracy claim is the alleged inducement of a breach of contract, the dismissal of the claim for inducement would also be fatal to the conspiracy claim.</P>
<P>10. As detailed below, the plaintiffs' claims against the Co-operators Group simply have no basis in fact or law.</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;THE FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>THE INVOLVEMENT OF CO-OPERATORS</TI>
<P>11. The first involvement by Co-operators in the events giving rise to this litigation was the receipt of a general enquiry from Deloitte LLP (&ldquo;Deloitte&rdquo;) in February 2009, asking whether Co-operators might be interested in acquiring an unnamed insurance brokerage. Co-operators expressed interest in the opportunity and, at the request of Deloitte, executed a confidentiality agreement.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of John Asher (&ldquo;Asher Affidavit&rdquo;), para. 8, Motion Record pg. 8.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>12. After the confidentiality agreement was executed, Deloitte identified the target as VISL and, in late February 2009, Co-operators received a presentation deck outlining VISL's business, in support of the proposed purchase opportunity. On March 9, 2009, Co-operators delivered a non-binding expression of interest to VCU to acquire the shares of VISL. Between March and July 2009, Co-operators engaged in a due diligence process with VCU regarding the proposed purchase.
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, para. 9, Motion Record, pg. 9.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>13. RSA/CNS had also been invited to pursue the purchase of VCU's shares of VISL and had participated in the very same process as Co-operators, but had been unwilling to offer a price that was competitive with that offered by Co-operators. By February 2009, the Plaintiffs were aware that VCU had retained Deloitte to assist it in actively seeking a buyer for VISL.
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, para. 10, Motion Record, pg. 9.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>14. Co-operators performed due diligence on VISL and learned, through the due diligence process, that VISL had broker agreements with various insurance companies for which it issued insurance policies, including non-exclusive broker agreements between CNS and VISL dated October 17, 1998 and between RSA and VISL, dated August 1, 2004. VISL represented to Co-operators that those broker agreements with RSA and CNS were the only current agreements with the Plaintiffs.
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, para. Hand Exhibit D, Motion Record, pg. 9.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>15. In a meeting between senior management at VCU and Co-operators on April 2, 2009, VCU advised that VISL had &ldquo;developed a branded program with CNS with a strategy to roll over all business from their other markets to this program....&rdquo; Co-operators was also expressly advised by VCU management that VISL did not have a current contract with CNS setting out the terms of that proposed new program.
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, para. 12, Motion Record, pg. 9 and Tab E, p. 106</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>16. During its due diligence investigation, Co-operators was provided with a copy of an unexecuted document entitled &ldquo;Insurance Program Agreement&rdquo; between CNS and VISL, which was unsigned and labelled &ldquo;Draft for Discussion Purposes&rdquo;.
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, para. 13, Motion Record pgs. 9-10 and Tab F.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>17. Co-operators was repeatedly assured by VCU that the draft Insurance Program Agreement had never been finalized, remained in a state of negotiation and was not binding on VISL. While relying on the representations of VCU and VISL that there was no binding agreement with RSA or CNS regarding the matters addressed in the draft Insurance Program Agreement, Co-operators prudently sought and obtained an indemnity from VCU against any claim to the contrary by RSA or CNS. Co-operators never encouraged or induced VISL to breach or abrogate any agreement between it and CNS or RSA.
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, paras. 14 and 15, Motion Record, pg. 10.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>THE SHARE PURCHASE AGREEMENT</TI>
<P>18. 708 Canada purchased the shares of VISL pursuant to a Share Purchase Agreement dated July 21, 2009. The shares were not purchased from VCU directly, but rather, were purchased from Citizens Bank of Canada, which acquired them from VCU prior to the close of the transaction.
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, paras. 16 and 17, Motion Record, pg. 10 and Tab G.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>19. At Section 5.3 of the Share Purchase Agreement, the vendors, YCU and Citizens Bank of Canada, represented that VISL was not bound by any material contract other than as disclosed in Schedule 5.3(12) of the Share Purchase Agreement. In that Schedule, VCU represented that the terms of VISL's relationship with CNS &ldquo;were never settled&rdquo;, but disclosed that CNS was asserting that there was a binding 5 year exclusivity commitment with a 2 year termination provision.
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, para. 18, Motion Record, pg. 10 and Tab G, pg. 244.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>20. While relying on VCU's assurance that it did not have a binding agreement with RSA/CNS, in light of the Plaintiffs' allegations to the contrary, Co-operators negotiated with VCU and obtained a full indemnity, reflected in Section 8.2(2) of the Share Purchase Agreement against the possibility of a claim being made by CNS or RSA in relation to the alleged contract.</P>
<P>21. Section 5.1(8)(a)(i) of the SPA contains a representation and warranty of VCU that &ldquo;the execution, delivery and performance by it of this Agreement and the completion of the Transactions will not (whether after the passage of time or notice or both) result in the breach or violation of any of the provisions of, or constitute a default under or conflict with ...any of its obligations under any Contract to which it is a party or by which any of its undertakings, property or assets is bound or affected.&rdquo; Section 1.1(33) of the SPA defines &ldquo;Contract&rdquo; as &ldquo;any agreement, contract, indenture, lease, deed of trust, licence, option, undertaking, promise or any other commitment or obligation, whether oral or written, express or implied, other than a Permit, and whether or not legally binding.&rdquo; Section 5.1 further acknowledges that the purchaser was relying on that representation and warranty. In the face of Section 5.1 it cannot be said that the Co-operators Group had any reason to believe that purchasing VISL would result in a breach of any agreement between VISL and RSA/CNS.</P>
<P>22. In entering the SPA, Co-operators' sole intention was to further its own economic interests by expanding its insurance brokerage business in British Columbia. Co-operators had no intention of interfering with or harming the interest of the Plaintiffs.
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, paras. 19 and 20, Motion Record, pg. 11, Tab G, pg. 229.and Tab K p.270-1, Q.767&ndash;769</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>PLAINTIFFS' EVIDENCE IN RESPONSE TO THIS MOTION</TI>
<P>23. The affidavit of Glen Pentland sworn June 17, 2015 on behalf of the Plaintiffs provides no support whatsoever to the bald allegations that members of the Co-operators Group participated in a conspiracy or committed the tort of inducing a breach of contract. Indeed, Mr. Pentland admits that he had no knowledge of the proposed sale of VISL to Co-operators until approximately 12 hours before it was announced.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Glen Pentland (&ldquo;Pentland Affidavit&rdquo;), para. 54, Responding Motion Record, Vol. 4 Tab B, pg. 20.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>24. The affidavit of Keith Mottram, similarly offers no evidence in support of the allegations against the Co-operators Group.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Keith Mottram (&ldquo;Mottram Affidavit&rdquo;) sworn June 18, 2015, Responding Motion Record, Vol. 4, Tab C.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>25. The Plaintiffs also filed the Affidavit of Steven Anthony Hayes (&ldquo;Hayes&rdquo;) of RSA/CNS. In paragraph 8 of that Affidavit, Hayes makes the bald assertion that &ldquo;shortly after their purchase of VISL closed, Co-op induced VISL to breach the Agreement by cancelling it without providing the required 2 years notice of the cancellation.&rdquo; He offers no evidence in support of that bald assertion. The evidence is in fact to the contrary. The only agreements which Co-operators terminated, were the non-exclusive written broker agreements attached as Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo; to the affidavit of John Asher filed in support of this motion. Those broker agreements were terminated in accordance with their terms and there is no allegation of a breach of those agreements.
<P1><BOLD>Affidavit of Hayes (&ldquo;Hayes Affidavit&rdquo;) sworn June 10, 2015, para. 8,</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Responding Motion Record, Vol. 1.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, Motion Record, Tab D.</BOLD></P1>
<P1><BOLD>Mottram Affidavit, Responding Motion Record, Vol. 4, Tabs C4 and C5.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>26. In paragraph 90 of the Hayes Affidavit, Hayes asserts that VISL and VCU had decided in December 2008 that &ldquo;they were not going to proceed with settling the contract terms&rdquo; because of their decision to explore the market the sell VISL. That is an important admission as it would be impossible to find that the Co-operators Group induced VISL to not proceed to finalize the contract if, as alleged by Hayes on behalf of the Plaintiffs, VCU had already decided to go to market and to cause VISL not to proceed to settle that contract prior to any involvement of the Co-operators Group.
<P1><BOLD>Hayes Affidavit, Responding Motion Record, Vol. 1, para. 90, Tab A, pg. 37.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>27. Hayes further admits that RSA/CNS was aware of VCU's intention to sell VISL and participated in the same auction process as Co-operators by appointing a friendly broker, Hub, to bid, in the hope that VISL would be purchased by Hub, which would pursue and maintain the program which RSA/CNS had been negotiating with VISL. RSA/CNS's efforts to move forward with the proposed program during the first half of 2009 were made in the hope that Hub would be the successful bidder, but obviously with knowledge that a different outcome was possible.
<P1><BOLD>Hayes Affidavit, Responding Motion Record, Vol. 1, paras. 99 to 115.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>28. A large number of undertakings were given on the examination for discovery of Hayes on March 25, 2014. Those undertakings included a request for particulars of the evidence relied upon to support the allegation that the Co-operators Group induced a breach of agreement and that the Co-operators Group knew of any such agreement. A similar undertaking was given to specify what was relied upon by the Plaintiffs to support the allegation that the Co-operators Group joined in a conspiracy, assisted VCU or VISL in maintaining an illusion of normal business and/or misrepresenting their true intentions as alleged in paragraph 20 of the Amended Statement of Claim.
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, Motion Record, Exhibit L, Tab L, pg. 284.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>29. At the time this motion was brought, no answers had been received to the undertakings notwithstanding several requests for same. Although the Plaintiffs eventually answered the undertakings, the answers to the questions noted above were not entirely responsive and, in any event, amounted to no more than an assertion that the Co-operators Group was aware of the draft Agreement and of the dispute between RSA/CNS and VISL as to whether they had a binding agreement for the new program and, therefore, appreciated that there was a risk associated with the uncertainty surrounding the legal status of the negotiations between those parties.
<P1><BOLD>Asher Affidavit, Motion Record, Tab L, pg. 284 and answers to undertakings on the examination for discovery of Hayes.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;ISSUES</TI>
<P>30. Is there any basis for the allegation that the Co-operators Group induced VISL to breach an agreement with the Plaintiff?</P>
<P>31. Is there any basis for the allegation that the Co-operators Group participated in an actionable conspiracy?</P></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV&mdash;THE LAW AND ARGUMENT</TI>
<BLOCK2><N>A.</N><TI>The Test for Summary Judgment</TI>
<P>32. The Co-operators Group submits that the test forsummary judgment has been firmly established by the Supreme Court of Canada in <CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak vs. Mauldin</SOC></CASEREF>, and that the issues raised on this motion are amenable to summary judgment under that test.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hryniak vs. Mauldin</SOC><CITE>2014 SCC7</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>.</BOLD></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>B.</N><TI>Inducing Breach of Contract</TI>
<P>33. The Co-operators Group did not participate in the negotiations between VISL and RSA/CNS and is not in a position to determine whether they entered a binding agreement. As indicated above, Co-operators Group relied on the representations of VCU that there was no binding agreement. Co-operators Group defers to the submissions made on behalf of VCU and 2421593 Canada Inc. in their motion for summary judgment on that issue.</P>
<P>34. It is well established that the elements of the tortof inducing breach of contract are:
<P1>(a) The defendant had knowledge of the contract between the plaintiff and the third party;</P1>
<P1>(b) The defendant's conduct was intended to cause the third party to breach the contract;</P1>
<P1>(c) T he defendant's conduct caused the third party to breach the contract; and</P1>
<P1>(d) T he plaintiff suffered damage as a result of the breach.</P1>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Correia vs. Canac Kitchens</SOC><YEAR>2008</YEAR><CITE>91 OR 3rd 353</CITE><COURTJUR>CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD><EM>at para. 99</EM>.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>35. On the evidence, it is clear that the Co-operators Group did not have knowledge of the alleged agreement between the Plaintiffs and VISL. The Co-operators Group was assured throughout by VCU that there was no binding contract. The Co-operators Group was not in a position to assess the merits of the representations being made to it in that regard and was entitled to rely on the assurances it received from VCU. Further, it is clear that nothing done by the Co-operators Group in responding to the request for bids or in entering the SPA was in any way intended to cause VISL to breach the alleged agreement. Further, on the Plaintiffs' own admission in the Hayes Affidavit, the conduct of the Co-operators Group did not cause VISL to breach the alleged agreement. To the contrary, that agreement, if it existed, was breached when VCU chose to go to market to sell its shares of VISL.</P>
<P>36. The case at bar has some parallels with the decision of the Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Harry Winton Investments Ltd. vs. CIBC Development Corp.</SOC></CASEREF> In that case, the plaintiff landlord decided to rent space to an abortion clinic. The defendant, Padulo, had been the major tenant in the building and objected to the landlord's decision and took the position that it constituted a breach of its lease entitling it to terminate the lease. The landlord disputed the tenant's position. The tenant commenced an action for a declaration that the lease was terminated and retained an agent to seek out new premises for it. The day after the action was commenced, the tenant met with the president of CIBC Development Corporation (&ldquo;Development&rdquo;) to discuss leasing new premises. A few months later, Padulo signed a new lease with Development. The former landlord sued Development for inducing breach of contract. On motion by Development, summary judgment was granted dismissing the action against it. The Court of Appeal stated as follows:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>The plaintiff's position appears to be that once Development became aware of the lease between the plaintiff and Padulo, Development was obliged to satisfy itself that Padulo had good grounds in law to establish a breach of the lease by the plaintiff before it, Development, could agree to rent to Padulo. As put by Mr. Morin (counsel for the plaintiff/appellant), once Development became aware of the contemporaneous settlement negotiations between plaintiff and Padulo, it was obliged to &ldquo;back off&rdquo;.</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>The motions judge held that this was not a correct view. As he said (at para 9): &ldquo;It is not for Development to adjudicate the legitimacy of the claim of breach. To suggest otherwise would make the negotiating of commercial leases virtually impossible.&rdquo;....In our view, because Development approached Padulo and offered to lease space to it at a time that Padulo had already decided to breach its contract with the appellant, there can be no liability. The possibility of liability could only arise if Padulo had not yet decided to terminate its lease and had been approached by Development to consider new premises....</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>A similar point was made by Mandel J. in</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Zander vs. Canac Kitchens Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[1988] O.J. No. 2105</CITE></CASEREF><BOLD>, where he pointed out that one must differentiate &ldquo;between the third party who in making the inconsistent dealing has merely taken advantage of the voluntary decision already of the (contract breaker) to discontinue his contract and the third party who has in fact been instrumental in bringing about the breach&rdquo;.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Harry Winton Investments Ltd. vs. CIBC Development Corp.</SOC><YEAR>2001</YEAR><CITE>52 OR 3rd 417</CITE></CASEREF></P1></P>
<P>37. As in the <EM>Harry Winton Investments</EM> case, there was no obligation on the Co-operators Group to determine which of RSA/CNS and VISL was correct. The evidence of the Plaintiffs is that VCU had decided to sell its interest and to not proceed to finalize the proposed agreement with RSA/CNS prior to any involvement by the Co-operators Group. In the circumstances, there can be no liability for inducing a breach of contract.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><N>C.</N><TI>The Law of Conspiracy</TI>
<P>38. There is simply no evidence to support the alleged agreement between the Defendants. Further, there is no basis for a finding of conspiracy as a matter of law.</P>
<P>39. It is well established that the elements of the tort of conspiracy are as follows:<QUOTE><P><BOLD>The constituent elements of the tort of conspiracy are: (1) two or more defendants make an agreement to injure the plaintiff; (2) the defendants (a) use some means (lawful or unlawful) for the predominant purpose of injuring the plaintiff, or (b) use unlawful means with knowledge that their acts were aimed at the plaintiff and knowing or constructively knowing that their acts would result in injury to the plaintiff; (3) the defendants act in furtherance of their agreement to injure; and (4) the plaintiff suffers damages as a result of the defendants' conduct.</BOLD></P></QUOTE>
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Jevco Insurance Company vs. Pacific Assessment Centre Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 7751</CITE><COURTJUR>Div.Ct.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> <BOLD>at para. 18.</BOLD></P1></P>
<P>40. In the case at bar the Plaintiffs do not suggest that there was an agreement to injure the Plaintiffs or that the defendants had the predominant purpose of injuring the Plaintiffs. To the contrary, they appear to allege that the defendants used unlawful means with knowledge that their acts were aimed at the Plaintiffs and that their acts would result in injury to the Plaintiffs. Quite apart from the fact that there is no evidence of any such agreement, the only allegedly</P>
<P>unlawful act which the Plaintiffs have identified as against the Co-operators Group is the inducing of a breach of contract. Accordingly, if there is no such inducement, there is no conspiracy.</P></BLOCK2></BLOCK1>
<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="V">PART V&mdash;ORDER REQUESTED</TI>
<P>41. The Co-operators Group therefore requests that summary judgment be granted dismissing this action as against them with costs.</P>
