<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;INTRODUCTION</TI>
<P>1. The issue in this action reads like a first-year law school contracts examination question. It asks: Can there be a binding agreement when the parties intend there to be a binding agreement, announce to the insurance industry the fact of the agreement, agree on the essential terms of that agreement and jointly perform that agreement for over 12 months.</P>
<P>2. From July 2008 to May 2009 VCI performed the Program Agreement (defined herein). It was only after VCU entered into the agreement to sell VCI to the Co-operators Group Limited (&ldquo;Co-op&rdquo;) that VCI, for the first time, attempted to resile from the Program Agreement, having determined, as a result of the sale, it was not in its economic interest to be bound by the Program Agreement. Although VCU sold VCI, it agreed to indemnify VCI and Co-op if the Program Agreement was binding on VCI. VCU and VCI are now, as a result, cynically trying to avoid liability for the Program Agreement.</P>
<P>3. VCU and VCI would have this Court accept that VCI took a substantial commercial risk without an agreement in place, and would have this court ignore the actual facts, given by actual participants as to the formation, terms and implementation of that agreement and the subsequent actions of VCI in avoiding the finalization of the written agreement. The evidence of the participants in this process for both RSA/CNS and VCI, is further supported by the contemporaneous documents.</P>
<P>4. VCU and VCI's position that there is no agreement must be seen in the light of VCU's decision in December 2008 to sell VCI, its subsequent steps to delay responding to the Draft Insurance Program Agreement (defined herein), and its desire to avoid the financial consequences resulting from the sale of VCI to Co-op.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;SUMMARY</TI>
<P>5. Prior to July 2008, RSA/CNS had been a non-exclusive supplier of home or &ldquo;habitational&rdquo; insurance products to Vancity Insurance Services Ltd. (&ldquo;VCI&rdquo;, now renamed 2421593 Canada Ltd. &ldquo;242&rdquo;), an insurance broker and wholly owned subsidiary of Vancouver City Savings Credit Union (&ldquo;VCU&rdquo;), pursuant to agreements that, among other things, provided a 20% commission rate for habitational insurance and a 90 day or 12 month notice for termination. RSA/CNS along with a number of other insurers including Sovereign General, Intact and Aviva, provided habitational insurance policies to VCI's approximately 20,000 customers.</P>
<P>6. In July of 2008, VCI announced to its employees and to the other insurers writing habitational policies for its customers, that after a selection process, RSA/CNS had been chosen to be its exclusive supplier of habitational insurance to its customers.</P>
<P>7. In two meetings in July and September 2008, VCI and RSA/CNS (sometimes jointly referred to as the &ldquo;Parties&rdquo;) confirmed terms offered at prior meetings, and negotiated and agreed to enter into a new agreement, the essential terms of which were;
<P1>(a) RSA/CNS would be the exclusive habitational insurance provider for VCI's approximately 20,000 clients;</P1>
<P1>(b) the agreement would be for a 5 year term;</P1>
<P1>(c) the agreement was to be cancellable on 2 years notice;</P1>
<P1>(d) RSA/CNS would pay a 25% commission rate when the Program was fully implemented, rather than the standard 20%;</P1>
<P1>(e) RSA/CNS would pay an interim commission rate of 23% until the Program was fully implemented;</P1>
<P1>(f) RSA/CNS would pay a further one time commission of 5%on each policy as it rolled over from VCI's previous insurers;</P1>
<P1>(g) RSA/CNS and VCI would together design a custom insurance product that VCI would offer to its customers; and</P1>
<P1>(h) In the case that one of VCI's insurers, after being advised of the new exclusive relationship with RSA/CNS, prematurely canceled VCI's ability to write and renew business for that insurer, RSA/CNS would fill that void and offer an insurance product from RSA/CNS to those customers.</P1>
<P1>(collectively the &ldquo;<BOLD>Program Agreement</BOLD>&rdquo;)</P1></P>
<P>8. From July 2008 to September 2009, although there was no written, signed agreement, RSA/CNS and VCI acted for all purposes as if their relationship was governed by the Program Agreement. RSA/CNS and VCI announced their new relationship to the world, jointly developed the first generation of the custom habitational insurance policy sold to VCI's customers, worked together to transfer or &ldquo;rollover&rdquo; approximately 9,000 insurance policies from VCI's other insurers, and made the decisions (for example underwriting and pricing decisions required for the rollover of each book of business from the different insurers) that were required in order to enable the rollover. In addition RSA/CNS paid for the rollover technology expenses and the project management costs agreed to in the Program Agreement. From July 2008 until July 2009 VCI and RSA/CNS worked together, harmoniously and without issue, to implement the Program Agreement.</P>
<P>9. However, in or about December of 2008, without the knowledge of RSA/CNS, VCU determined that it wished to sell VCI and thereafter embarked on what was initially a secret process that ultimately led to the sale of VCI to a direct competitor of RSA/CNS. RSA/CNS learned of the sale in May of 2009 although it was not advised of the identity of the purchaser until the public announcement of the sale in July, 2009 (&ldquo;the July Announcement&rdquo;) when VCU advised that VCI had been sold to Co-op. The sale to Co-op closed in September 2009. The work required to continue implementing the Program Agreement continued throughout the December 2008 to July 2009 period, as those VCI employees on the forefront of the implementation were not advised that VCU was trying to sell VCI.</P>
<P>10. Notwithstanding that it had operated as if there was an agreement for more than 12 months, following the advice to RSA/CNS of the sale of VCI in May, 2009, VCU took the position with RSA/CNS <EM>for the first time</EM> that as there was no signed agreement there was no binding agreement.</P>
<P>11. Following the closing of the sale of VCI to Co-op in September, 2009, Co-op through its subsidiary Federated, advised RSA/CNS that as of September 10, 2009, it would no longer be supplying habitational insurance products to VCI, and purported to terminate the relationship between RSA/CNS and VCI by terminating not the Program Agreement but prior non-exclusive insurer/broker agreements.</P>
<P>12. VCI and VCU are now taking the position that it was agreed by the Parties that there would be no binding agreement unless there was a written, signed agreement. However, there is no mention of such a pre-condition in any of the dealings between RSA/CNS and VCI during the RFI process and the contract meetings in July and September. VCI has provided no support for its assertion, and VCI's own actions from July 2008 to March 2009 belie that assertion. This is simply an attempt by VCI and VCU to avoid VCI's contractual responsibilities following the sale of VCI to Co-op.</P>
<P>13. VCI now takes the position that essential terms of the Agreement were not agreed to by the Parties.</P>
<P>14. In fact there is overwhelming evidence, not dependent on the credibility of any witness, that the Parties entered into the Program Agreement and worked for over 12 months to implement it. Throughout the period VCI had the benefit of an increased commission structure, an enhanced habitational policy to offer to its customers, and the other benefits of the exclusive relationship with RSA/CNS provided for in the Program Agreement. VCI and VCU only resiled from the Program Agreement once it decided that the Program Agreement was not in its best interest. VCU recognized that it was not in its economic interest and it could decrease the value of VCI, if VCI was subject to the Program Agreement.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">PART III&mdash;THE FACTS</TI>
<BLOCK3><TI>THE WITNESSES</TI>
<P>15. VCI has not filed any affidavit evidence of any witness from VCI or VCU on this motion for summary judgment. The witness produced by VCI and VCU on discovery had essentially no knowledge of the negotiation of the Program Agreement, its terms, or its implementation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Examinations for Discovery of Rick Sielski, Q.'s 24, 36, 39-40, 88, 126&ndash;129, 203&ndash;226, 238, 312, 315-316, 394&ndash;477.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. RSA/CNS has filed affidavits from 3 witnesses each of whom had personal involvement in either the negotiation of the Program Agreement or its implementation.</P>
<P>17. Tony Hayes (&ldquo;Hayes&rdquo;) was one of the two most senior people involved for RSA/CNS during the RFI process, and the negotiation of the Program Agreement. He left his employment with RSA in 2014 and is now the CEO of Vancouver Island Insurance Centres, a large insurance brokerage on Vancouver Island.</P>
<P>18. Glen Pentland (&ldquo;Pentland&rdquo;) was, at the relevant time, the Business Development Manager for VCI. He was intimately involved in the negotiation of the Program Agreement, and headed up the day to day implementation of the Program Agreement on behalf of VCI. He worked closely with Terry Taciuk the President of VCI (&ldquo;Taciuk&rdquo;). When VCI was sold to Co-op he was then employed by Federated Agencies (Co-op's BC agency and a defendant in this lawsuit), leaving in April 2012. He is now employed as Marketing Manager with British Columbia Automobile Association.</P>
<P>19. Keith Mottram (&ldquo;Mottram&rdquo;) worked at RSA for 36 years, retiring in July 2013. He had responsibility for managing the transfer or &ldquo;rollover&rdquo; of insurance business under the Program Agreement, from VCI's other insurers to RSA/CNS.</P>
<P>20. In paragraphs 46 and 47 of the VCI Factum counsel makes serious allegations of impropriety in the preparation of the affidavit material relied upon by RSA/CNS. He alleges that the material was &ldquo;carefully crafted&rdquo; by RSA/CNS's counsel over the &ldquo;full year taken to come up with the affidavits&rdquo;. Counsel is fully aware that a significant part of the delay occurred as a result of the untimely death of Theodor Kerzner, requiring among other things, the retainer of other co-counsel to assist in this matter.</P>
<P>21. In addition, the actions of the Parties and the documentary evidence is consistent with and supports the evidence of Hayes, Pentland and Mottram. There is no evidence offered by VCI or VCU to support their position that no agreement was reached.</P>
<P>22. The one important witness that this Court has not heard from is Taciuk. He was the driving force at VCI, behind the move to a single source insurer that culminated in the Program Agreement. In addition as is clear from the documents, he was actively misleading RSA/CNS about the status of the Draft Insurance Program Agreement.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>BACKGROUND</TI>
<P>23. Since at least 1998 there had been an ongoing non-exclusive, insurer-broker relationship between CNS as insurer and VCI as broker. This agreement provided, among other things, a commission rate of 20%, was non-exclusive, and contained a 12 month notice of termination by the broker.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Supplementary Motion Record (&ldquo;SMR&rdquo;), Tab 1</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (the &ldquo;1998 Agreement&rdquo;) It did not provide for a signing bonus, a rollover bonus or a CNS deposit, or a 5 year term.</P>
<P>24. Since at least 2004 there had been an ongoing non-exclusive, insurer-broker relationship between RSA as insurer and VCI as broker. This agreement provided, among other things, a commission rate of 20%, was non-exclusive, and contained a 90 day notice of termination by the broker.
<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Supplementary Motion Record, Tab 2</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (the &ldquo;2004 Agreement&rdquo; and collectively with the 1998 Agreement the &ldquo;Old Agreements&rdquo;) It did not provide for a signing bonus, a rollover bonus or a CNS deposit, or a 5 year term.</P>
<P>25. CNS was purchased by RSA in January 2008.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RSA/CNS Responding Motion Record (&ldquo;RMR&rdquo;), Volume 1, Tab A, Affidavit of Stephen Anthony Hayes (&ldquo;Hayes Affidavit&rdquo;), Para. 12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>26. In February 2008, RSA/CNS received a &ldquo;Request for Interest&rdquo; from VCI for the provision of &ldquo;new, innovative insurance products&rdquo; (&ldquo;the &ldquo;RFI&rdquo;). The RFI was issued following approval given to VCI by VCU's Executive Team to pursue a single insurer partnership, an idea promoted by Taciuk. In the RFI, VCI stated it was pursuing a &ldquo;unique and bold strategy&rdquo; to enter into an exclusive relationship with one insurer rather then the industry standard broker/insurer model where a broker works with multiple insurers.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Hayes Affidavit, Volume 1, Tab A, Para. 13, 14, 18, Ex. 1; RMR, Volume 4, Tab B <UNDER>Affidavit of Glen Pentland</UNDER>, (&ldquo;Pentland Affidavit&rdquo;) Para. 11, 12, 17 and 18, Ex. A.; Examination for Discovery of Rick Sielski, Q.'s 21&ndash;25.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>27. RSA/CNS responded to the RFI and among other terms proposed a &ldquo;partnership&rdquo; with a 5-year commitment and an increase in the standard commission rate from 20% to 25%. Upon receipt of RSA/CNS's response, VCI requested further information from RSA/CNS in a &ldquo;Request for Proof of Concept&rdquo;. RSA/CNS responded with a &ldquo;Proof of Concept&rdquo; outlining in more detail its proposal for a 5 year &ldquo;partnership&rdquo; with increased commission from 20% to 25%, profit sharing, a 5% bonus paid on policy transfer and a minimum of a 6 month cancellation period. RSA/CNS and VCI met on June 10, 2008 to discuss the Proof of Concept (the &ldquo;Proof of Concept Meeting&rdquo;).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Paras. 15, 16, 17, 18, Ex. 2, 3, 4, 5; Pentland Affidavit, Paras. 13, 14, Ex. B, C.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. Before choosing RSA/CNS, VCI needed to be comfortable that RSA/CNS were committed to the unique arrangement. Throughout the RFI process VCI highlighted the vulnerability and risk assumed by VCI by entering into a single insurer relationship. Consolidating a broker's portfolio to a single insurer is uncommon in the industry because of the risk of a broker relying on one insurer for underwriting and pricing competitiveness across a wide spread of risks. Insurers from time to time stop writing certain classes of business, increase prices as markets harden and vary the level of service they provide to brokers depending on their internal efficiency initiatives. Because brokers are dependent on insurers to underwrite their portfolio of risks, brokers generally avoid single insurer relationships to protect against the risks listed above, and the fear of insurers marketing directly to consumers, which can negatively impact the growth and profitability of their brokerage. As a result of this concern, VCI wanted RSA/CNS to agree to a long termination period if it wanted to cancel the new relationship because of the risks it faced.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 4, Pentland Affidavit, paras 17&ndash;21;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>29. During the Proof of Concept Meeting, according to Pentland, VCI expressed the desire for a five year term, a two-year rehabilitation period (if any problems occurred in the relationship or there was a deteriorating loss ratio) and a 12 month notice of termination period starting after the two-year rehabilitation period. VCI felt that these terms would protect it from some of the risk associated with a single insurer arrangement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 4, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 13, 14, Ex. B, C; Hayes Affidavit, Paras. 15, 16, 17, 18, Ex. 2, 3, 4, 5.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> RSA/CNS's notes following this meeting record that VCI asked for a notice of termination of 12 months.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 4, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 21; Hayes Affidavit, Para. 18, 19., Ex 6</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>30. Following the Proof of Concept Meeting, VCI asked for and was given approval by VCU's leadership to proceed with the RSA/CNS partnership. In late June, 2008 VCI telephoned RSA/CNS to advise that RSA/CNS had been selected to enter into negotiations to be their exclusive habitational provider and the parties arranged to meet on July 3, 2008.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 4, Pentland Affidavit, Paras. 15, 23; Hayes Affidavit, Para. 21, Pentland cx, pages 4-5</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>THE JULY 3, 2008 MEETING</TI>
<P>31. The meeting on July 3, 2008 (the &ldquo;July 3 Meeting&rdquo;) was attended by, among others, Keenan and Hayes for RSA/CNS and Taciak and Pentland for VCI. The evidence of the Parties and the minutes clearly show that the parties at the meeting set out agreements reached and the future steps to implement their new relationship.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit. Paras. 23, 24, 25, 26, 27, 28; RMR Volume 4, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 23, Ex. D, E.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>32. At the July 3 meeting, in order to respond to VCI's concerns, RSA/CNS confirmed that in addition to a 5 year term, it would agree to a 12 month termination provision rather then the 6 month period set out in the Proof of Concept.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Paras. 19, 31.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>33. In addition to the 5 year term and 12 month termination provision, VCI and RSA/CNS agreed at the July 3 Meeting, that:
<P1>(a) RSA/CNS would be VCI's exclusive supplier of habitational insurance;</P1>
<P1>(b) RSA/CNS and VCI would together design a custom habitational insurance product to be offered to VCI's customers which in July 2008, was anticipated to be available as of January 1, 2009;</P1>
<P1>(c) Commission was to increase in accordance with the proposal in the Proof of Concept-25% when the Program was in full effect;</P1>
<P1>(d) RSA/CNS would pay a bonus of 5% upon the rollover of each insurance policy;</P1>
<P1>(e) VCI would receive 25% profit sharing, an increase from the standard 10%;</P1>
<P1>(f) RSA/CNS would dedicate 1% of premium volume to marketing;</P1>
<P1>(g) RSA/CNS would pay the technology costs necessary for the rollover;</P1>
<P1>(h) Both VCI and RSA/CNS would hire project managers to manage the project;</P1>
<P1>(i) VCI and RSA/CNS agreed that the agreement of their &ldquo;partnership&rdquo; would be announced on July 8, 2008; and</P1>
<P1>(j) RSA/CNS would coordinate the rollover of VCI's existing business to RSA/CNS, in order to ensure VCI's business was protected if there was an insurer backlash/cancellation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Paras. 26, 27, 28, 29, 30, 31; Pentland Affidavit, Para. 26, Ex. E., CX Hayes pages 23-24</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>34. The evidence of the terms of the agreement reached at the July 3 Meeting comes from Hayes and Pentland. The Minutes of the July 3 meeting were prepared by Pentland. They both offer consistent evidence as to what was agreed. There is simply no evidence that the terms agreed to were other then what is set out in paragraph 32 above. The only difference in their evidence is that Mr. Pentland believes that the VCI's request for a 2+ year termination notice began at the Proof of Concept Meeting and continued at the July 3 Meeting, whereas the RSA/CNS document marked as Exhibit &ldquo;6&rdquo; to Hayes affidavit shows that VCI wanted a rehabilitation term and to extend the termination notice period to 12 months from the 6 months offered by RSA/CNS at that time. In fact Hayes' evidence was that at the July 3 Meeting the 12 month termination notice requested by VCI, was confirmed by RSA/CNS. In the end because of the agreement reached at the September 11 Meeting this evidentiary difference is irrelevant.</P>
<P>35. Throughout the discussions in June and at the July 3 Meeting, VCI expressed a concern about the effect that the exclusive arrangement with RSA/CNS would have on the other insurers that, at that time, wrote habitational insurance for VCI's customers. VCI was concerned that those insurers, on being advised that VCI had entered into an exclusive relationship with RSA/CNS, would cancel their agreements with VCI and stop writing policies before the RSA/CNS custom product was available. In order to address this concern, VCI and RSA/CNS agreed at the July 3 Meeting that, if an insurer cancelled, the project timeline would be accelerated and RSA/CNS would provide their current insurance policy for VCI to offer to its customers pending the development of the custom product to be jointly developed.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 28, 31, Ex. 11; Pentland Affidavit, Paras. 25, 26, Ex. E.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>36. In cross-examination Pentland had the following to say about the agreement that he says was reached at the July 3 Meeting:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>...in those conversations we had with CNS, there was commitments from us in terms of rolling the portfolio, a 5% commission, an additional 5% commission so that we would be up from 20 to 25 over a period of time, an additional 5 percent override, a five year term, and the piece that's not really articulated is the commitment piece because of the risk that we were taking on...that was a big part of our discussion in every step of the way. With each of the insurers that we deal with the discussion was we are going out on a limb in terms of risk, and so the need for that security in the process of doing that...within a couple of days [of the July 3 Meeting] we were talking to partners, and we were expressing that we had an agreement with CNS as our sole distributor...this wasn't something where an insurer, CNS, would cancel on us in 30 day&mdash;60 or 90 days...&rdquo; (GP CX pages 13 and 14)</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>For most of the remuneration in terms of commissions was fairly locked down. Override commission was locked down. Marketing support and that stuff was locked down. (ex 33/18&ndash;21)</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Pentland Cross-Examination, Pages 13 and 14, Page 33, L. 18&ndash;21.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>FOLLOWING JULY 3, 2008 MEETING</TI>
<P>37. Following the July 3 Meeting, Taciak and Pentland met with VCI's other insurers including Sovereign General and Intact, and told them that RSA/CNS had been chosen as the exclusive habitational insurance provider, to commence January 1, 2009, and that VCI would be cancelling its agreements with those insurers.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 32; Pentland Affidavit, Paras, 27, 28;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>38. VCI would not have advised the other insurance companies if it did not believe it had a binding agreement with RSA/CNS on the essential terms of the Program Agreement, following the July 3 Meeting. VCI recognized that &ldquo;there was no going back&rdquo; once VCI had announced its &ldquo;partnership&rdquo; with RSA/CNS to its other insurers. Pentland, on cross-examination did not agree with VCI's current position that out of the July 3 Meeting there had to further discussion to &ldquo;move towards a definitive agreement that would be signed by both parties&rdquo;...and said:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>...I would say no. Because out of July 3 for us to go to our other insurers and say, we're going to cancel our agreement with you, we needed total certainty that we had a partner on board. It wasn't a case of the existing contract the existing arrangements...we need assurances. So we had Ken Keenan absolutely committing that yes, we were there for you. We're going to put this together. There's some details that we don't know about it, but there was a lot of stuff that we had talked about. We were pretty confident, yeah, that works, that works, that works, that works. But the piece around&mdash;you know, was it loose? Absolutely not. Because there is no way I could go to those insurers and say, I'm going to cancel my agreement with you.</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 4, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 31, Cross Examination of Glen Pentland, p. 15, L. 8&ndash;24.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>39. One of VCI's insurers, Sovereign General (&ldquo;SG&rdquo;), on being advised of the new agreement with RSA/CNS, gave VCI immediate notice that, as of July 10, 2008, VCI could no longer bind SG for new habitational insurance policies and, as of October 10, 2008, VCI could no longer renew SG policies. This immediate cancellation, although a foreseen risk, caused an acceleration of the implementation of the Program Agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 37, 38; Pentland Affidavit, Paras. 29, 30, 31.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>40. In accordance with the Program Agreement, each of VCI and RSA/CNS announced the new relationship to their employees on July 8, 2008. In its written announcement to its employees, VCI described the risks associated with entering in to an exclusive arrangement with one insurer and expressed its belief that &ldquo;<BOLD>Both Vancity Insurance and [RSA/CNS] have tied our fates together and so working together is imperative</BOLD>&rdquo; and that &ldquo;<BOLD>RSA/CNS had a much stronger recognition...that this endeavor would require a high degree of partnership and shared commitments</BOLD>.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 33, 34, Ex. 12, 13; Pentland Affidavit, Para. 32, 33, 34, Ex. G, H.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>41. On July 14, 2008 VCI formally announced to VCU that it had entered in to a &ldquo;meaningful, long term partnership with a large national insurer&rdquo; with RSA/CNS. There is no evidence whatsoever, that any VCI or VCU employee questioned that an announcement was made without there being a written, signed contract or that it was made without essential terms of that agreement not being reached.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 39, Ex. 17; Pentland Affidavit, Para. 35, Ex I.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>42. Between the announcements referred to above and September 11, 2008 the Parties had many meetings and made many decisions, in order to proceed with the now accelerated implementation of the Program Agreement, including meetings on July 15, 2008 entitled the &ldquo;Rollover Planning Session&rdquo; attended by Pentland and Mottram, July 24, 2008 entitled the Vancity Brovada Rollover Project called by Mottram, and a meeting on August 5, 2008 entitled Program Project Status Update attended by Mottram. These are just 3 of the meetings that demonstrate that the Parties were operating under the Program Agreement and implementating the Program Agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Paras. 40&ndash;48, Ex. 18&ndash;27; RMR Volume 4, Tab B Pentland Affidavit, Paras. 36&ndash;46, Ex. F, J, K, L, M, N; RMA Volume 4, Tab C, Mottram Affidavit, Paras. 12&ndash;18, Exs. 1, 2 and 3</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>THE SEPTEMBER 11 MEETING</TI>
<P>43. VCI and RSA/CNS met on September 11, 2008 (the &ldquo;September 11 Meeting&rdquo;) to further discuss their relationship.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 49; RMR Volume 4, Pentland Affidavit, Paras. 47&ndash;50, Ex. O.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>44. Notwithstanding that VCI and RSA/CNS had agreed to a 12 month termination provision at the July 3 Meeting, VCI wished to evidence a stronger commitment from RSA/CNS to the relationship and accordingly asked RSA/CNS at the September 11 Meeting to amend their previous agreement and to provide a two year rehabilitation period prior to the one year notice of termination. It was Hayes' undisputed evidence that after negotiation at the September 11 Meeting, the Parties agreed to extend the termination notice period to 2 years. In addition VCI and RSA/CNS agreed that the first year of the 2-year period would be a rehabilitation period where the parties would work together to solve the issues that caused notice to be given.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 53&ndash;55, 61, Volume 2, Ex. 30; RMR Volume 4, Tab B, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 49, Ex. O.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>45. Hayes acknowledged in his examination for discovery at Q 410 that prior to the September 11 meeting the Parties had not concluded an agreement on how the non-performance by 1 party would give the other party the right to terminate, contrary to was is stated in paragraph 33(i) of the Factum of VCU and VCI. This was the question asked and answered in the examination for discovery. There is no evidence that the Parties considered that this was an essential tem.</P>
<P>46. As the September 11 Meeting was in the context of SG's cancellation, VCI requested and RSA/CNS agreed to pay an &ldquo;interim&rdquo; commission on policies written until the full 25% commission came in to effect once the Program Agreement was fully implemented, which was anticipated at that time, to be January 1, 2009. RSA/CNS and VCI agreed that this interim commission would be 23%. There is no evidence that suggests that Hayes and Pentland are incorrect when they state that this was the agreement from the September 11 Meeting. VCI confirmed the that the 23% was agreed to at the September 11 Meeting in Pentland's email dated January 8, 2009 where he stated in his email to Tony Hayes &ldquo;...It was mine and Terry's understanding that the following was agreed to in the first discussion on the contract in early September...&rdquo;. Further evidence confirming that 23 % had been agreed to comes from the evidence of Co-op where they confirm that when they conducted their due diligence the commission rate they saw was 23%.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 56, 59, Volume 2, Ex. 42; RMR, Volume 4, Tab B, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 42, Ex. P., SMS, Tab 3A</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>47. In addition to the above VCI and RSA/CNS agreed at the September 11 Meeting:
<P1>(a) that the 5 year term would commence when the Program was fully implemented, which was still anticipated to be January 1, 2009;</P1>
<P1>(b) that RSA/CNS would pay an administrative allowance (draft agreement Sch &ldquo;E&rdquo; (d) to VCI of $135,000 and make a deposit of $5,000,000 with VCU, when the written agreement was signed;</P1>
<P1>(c) that RSA/CNS would make a one-time $50,000 payment towards Marketing Support (in addition to the 1% agreed to in the Proof of Concept); and</P1>
<P1>(d) RSA/CNS agreed to pay $56,000 towards the project manager for VCI.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Paras. 54, 55, 56, Volume 2, Ex 29, 30</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>48. The evidence as to the change in the termination provision and the additional terms of the agreement reached at the September Meeting came from Hayes, Pentland not having attended the meeting. Pentland did prepare the Contract Negotiations outline dated September 8, 2008. There is no evidence from VCI that the Parties did not agree to a 2 year termination provision or that the additional terms agreed to at the September 11 Meeting were other than is set out in paragraph 56 of Hayes' affidavit, which sets out, in addition, contract terms confirmed from the July 3 Meeting. In addition Hayes' note made after the September 11 Meeting confirms the agreement to extend the termination notice to 2 years with the 1<SUP>st</SUP> year to include rehabilitation.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, para 61, Volume 2, Ex. 30</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>49. At the September 11 Meeting, VCI and RSA/CNS determined that as they had agreed on the essential terms of their agreement, RSA/CNS would prepare and circulate a first draft of a written contract to reflect those terms. There was no agreement to prepare a Letter of Intent or the Spirit and Intent non-binding agreement referred to in in Exhibit 28 to Hayes' affidavit prepared by VCI before the September 11 Meeting, or is there any evidence that VCI or RSA/CNS was expecting one following the agreement that RSA/CNS would prepare the first draft of the written contract.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 57, Volume 2, Exhibit 28; RMR Volume 4, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 50.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>50. At no time however was there any discussion or agreement that a signed, written contract was a pre condition to an agreement between the Parties. The Parties behaviour after the July 3 Meeting and the September 11 Meeting clearly shows that they were implementing the Program Agreement.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>PERFORMANCE OF THE PROGRAM AGREEMENT</TI>
<P>51. From and after July 3, 2008 VCI and RSA/CNS acted in accordance with the Program Agreement.</P>
<P>52. They each made public and intra company announcements of the exclusive relationship as set out above.</P>
<P>53. The Parties had celebrations July 29, 2008, December 2008, and January 29, 2009 to celebrate their success and the formation of the relationship.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 66; RMR Volume 4, Tab B, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 53.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>54. Representatives of VCI including Pentland and RSA/CNS including Keith Mottram met on July 15, 2008 to begin to plan the rollover, it being a given that the rollover would happen. The Parties were working in each other's offices and working together day to day to implement the Project, carrying on as partners.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 4, RMR Volume 4, Tab B, Pentland Affidavit, Paras. 36&ndash;46, RMR, Volume 4, Tab C, Mottram Affidavit, Ex 1.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>55. VCI and RSA/CNS hired Project Managers; Paul Mittal for VCI and Laura Seto for RSA/CNS to implement the Program Agreement. RSA/CNS paid the $56,000 agreed to at the September 11 Meeting<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 4, Tab B, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 39, Ex 38.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>56. The Parties worked together on the Claims promise that formed part of the Program Agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 67; RMR Volume 4, Tab B Pentland Affidavit, Para. 41, Ex. M.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>57. RSA/CNS and VCI worked together to develop the computer programming required to roll over approximately 20,000 insurance policies from 5 or 6 different insurers to RSA/CNS. In this regard RSA/CNS retained and paid for the services of Brovada Technologies (as agreed) who provided the necessary software to implement the roll over of the thousands of insurance policies.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Exs. 63, 86; RMR Volume 4, Tab B, Pentland Affidavit, Paras. 37, 44, Ex. J.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>58. VCI and RSA/CNS worked together on the coverage, cost and underwriting requirements for the insurance policies and worked together to develop the first generation of the exclusive insurance product to be offered to VCI's customers. This product, referred to as &ldquo;Pure Home&rdquo; &ldquo;best of both&rdquo; or &ldquo;BOB&rdquo; (the &ldquo;Bob Policy&rdquo;)&rdquo; was completed and offered to VCI's customers after December 1, 2008.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 74, Ex. 37; RMR Volume 4, Tab B, Pentland Affidavit, Paras. 38, 40, 45.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>59. Discussions were commenced to increase VCI's penetration of the members of VCU as potential customers.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 4, Tab B Pentland Affidavit, Para. 43.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>60. The SG Rollover commenced October 1, 2008, for renewals dated on or after November 30, 2008. As was agreed at the July 3 Meeting, the first business was rolled over to the RSA insurance product. As of the December 1, 2008 former SG customers were offered the Bob Policy for renewals effective January 4, 2009. A form letter was agreed to that was to be sent to VCI's clients for renewal purposes which stated:
<QUOTE><P>This year I'm pleased to tell you that I'm moving your existing policy to our new Vancity Insurance policy that we've created with our partner, Canadian Northern Shield Insurance Company (CNS)<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 4, Tab 4, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 40, Ex. L. RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Paras. 73, 74, Exs. 36, 37, 78.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>61. In October 2008, Ing Insurance advised VCI that as of November 1, 2008, it would no longer accept new business and that effective February 18, 2009 it would no longer accept renewals. ING customers were rolled over to RSA/CNS policies for November 2008 renewals and as of January 5, 2009 were offered the Bob Policy.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 4, Tab B, Pentland Affidavit, Ex. L; RMR Volume 4, Tab C, Mottram Affidavit, Ex. 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>62. The Aviva Rollover commenced February 16, 2009.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 4, Tab C, Mottram Affidavit, Ex. 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>63. The Wawanesa Rollover commenced April 6, 2009.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 4, Tab C, Mottram Affidavit, Ex. 11.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>64. By September 2009, there had been approximately 9,000 insurance policies rolled over from other insurers to RSA/CNS.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 4, Tab C, Mottram Affidavit, Para. 26.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>THE WRITTEN CONTRACT</TI>
<P>65. In accordance with the agreement reached at the September 11 Meeting RSA/CNS prepared a first draft of the written agreement (the &ldquo;Draft Insurance Program Agreement&rdquo;) and sent it to VCI on December 1, 2008.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 76, Exs. 38, 39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>66. As had been agreed at the July 3 Meeting and the September 11 Meeting, the Draft Insurance Program Agreement provided that:
<P1>(a) CNS would be the exclusive supplier of habitational insurance products to VCI and VCU's customers (s. 9.01);</P1>
<P1>(b) Develop the Program&mdash;Schedule &ldquo;A&rdquo;;</P1>
<P1>(c) The Effective Date was to be January 1, 2009 (page 1);</P1>
<P1>(d) that the agreement was for a 5 year term (s. 14.01);</P1>
<P1>(e) that the agreement was terminable by either party on a minimum of 2 years written notice (s. 14.02);</P1>
<P1>(f) that the standard commission payable was 25% (Sch. E);</P1>
<P1>(g) that for marketing support CNS would pay VCI 1% of the premium payable annually and a one-time $50,000 (Sch. &ldquo;E&rdquo;)</P1>
<P1>(h) that CNS would pay $135,000 to VCI on signature of the written agreement (Sch. E);</P1>
<P1>(i) that CNS would maintain a minimum $5,000,000 deposit at VCU(Sch E.);</P1>
<P1>(j) that &ldquo;...the parties will work together to develop suitable servicelevels for the performance of Vancity's responsibilities under this Agreement (s. 3.04);</P1>
<P1>(k) that &ldquo;...the parties will work together to develop a technology solution agreeable to both Vancity Insurance and CNS that will allow premium rate generation and programming and electronic communication of data between Vancity Insurance and CNS...(s. 3.05 and Schedule &ldquo;H&rdquo;);</P1>
<P1>(l) Each Party shall appoint an individual or individuals...who shall be responsible for managing the relationship of the Party with the other Party and provision of the Program to Customers. (s. 4.10);</P1>
<P1>(m) &ldquo;the Parties shall actively collaborate on an ongoing basis to ensure the optimum design, development, execution and modification of the Program in order to best provide Customers with exceptional value through a distinctive combination of features, while maintaining the profitability of the Program...to that end, the Parties shall, in respect of each 12 month period during the Term, collaboratively develop and agreed upon business plan...which shall pertain to: (a) product features and rates; (b) sales underwriting and portfolio performance targets; and (c) marketing strategy...&rdquo;; (s. 4.02) and</P1>
<P1>(n) Claims Satisfaction Surveys were covered by Section 6 and Schedule &ldquo;D&rdquo; and Claims Services Standards are set out in Schedule &ldquo;C&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 39.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P1></P>
<P>67. RSA/CNS indicated to VCI in its letter dated December 1, 2008 that accompanied the Draft Insurance Program Agreement, that while the agreement reached at the September 11 Meeting contemplated the payment of the $135,000 &ldquo;signing bonus&rdquo; when the contract was signed, RSA/CNS was open to a discussion to pay it before December 31, 2008. The $135,000 was paid by RSA/CNS to VCI in December 2008.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 38.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>68. On December 11, 2008 Pentland circulated the Draft Insurance Program Agreement to employees at VCI asking for their input into certain sections and Schedules of the Draft Agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 60.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>RESPONSE TO DRAFT CONTRACT</TI>
<P>69. On December 12, 2008, in response to an email from RSA/CNS to VCI with respect to Sch. E of the Draft Agreement, Pentland advised:
<QUOTE><P>...what a detailed contract it is. I think it is close and Terry will be talking to Ken.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 80, Ex. 41.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>70. In a January 19, 2009 email Taciuk advised Rick Sielski a member of the Executive Committee of VCU that:
<QUOTE><P>FYI we have received some industry advice on our CNS contract however I am holding off sending this to our external lawyers so that we don't waste money given project Jet.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 48.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>71. On January 27, 2009, Mittal (VCI's project manager) asked Pentland about the status of the contract. Pentland then asked Taciuk who replied &ldquo;We are still waiting for our lawyers but I have been promised soon.&rdquo; However there is no evidence that Taciuk ever sent the draft contract for legal review.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 52.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>72. On February 10, 2009, Hayes sent Taciuk an email enquiring about the status of the contract. Taciuk immediately advised Sielski of the request and said:
<QUOTE><P>What I propose is that I tell Tony [Hayes] that we are close with the contract and that we will be getting back to them on &ldquo;x&rdquo; date that would be after you have pitched RSA. If that will be more then a week or two I will need a new plan.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 53.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>73. On February 11, 2009, Taciuk responded by e-mail to Hayes' follow up concerning the status of the contract review. This e-mail provides the only evidence that VCI disagreed with any of the terms of the Draft Insurance Program Agreement. He said:
<QUOTE><P>I guess we are even on having slow lawyers...There are a few areas where the contract appears to need more material changes for example it does contemplate Agency billing while our agreed plan is direct bill. We are also looking at providing frameworks for the appendices so that we can progress that as the next step.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 54.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>It is obvious from Taciuk's email where he highlights a small detail that he must have carefully read the Draft Insurance Program Agreement. It is very instructive that the only term he questions is this small detail.</P>
<P>74. In early March Pentland, again asked Taciuk about the status of the contract. Taciuk emailed Sielski on March 4, 2009 and said:
<QUOTE><P>I have also been hearing from the CNS President that he is getting heat because we don't yet have a contract.</P>
<P>I know where we are in our process. Any bright thoughts on how I can forestall? So far I am blaming this on our backed-up legal department and a corporate cost control edict not to use external legal counsel.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 55.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>75. On March 16, Taciuk advised Seliski that:
<QUOTE><P>FYI CNS is still looking for the contract. I am continuing to use legal backlogs as the reason for delay.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 57.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>76. On March 26, 2009, Taciuk advised Hayes that:
<QUOTE><P>Unfortunately the wheels of commerce are slow here at Vancity at the present time. I will provide you an update as soon as I receive one for [sic] our legal department.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 58.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>77. In none of this correspondence is there any indication of any disagreement with the essential terms of the Draft Insurance Program Agreement, as agreed in the July 3 Meeting and September 11 Meeting. Even with his desire to avoid finalizing in writing the Program Agreement, Taciuk did not suggest there was anything incorrect in the Draft Insurance Program Agreement with respect to the essential terms&mdash;he only referred to a change being required to show that the agreed plan was to direct bill the clients not agency bill, a very small part of the administrative services set out in the Draft Insurance Program Agreement to be provided by VCI under section 3.01.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 54.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>78. In addition, these foregoing paragraphs make it clear that VCI had no intention of finalizing the Draft Insurance Program Agreement. Instead, it led RSA/CNS (and its own employees) to believe that memorialization of the Program Agreement was proceeding. With the exception of one comment from Taciuk, no feedback was received by RSA/CNS indicating that there were any concerns about the Draft Insurance Program Agreement. Now, in this motion VCI attempts to use that foot dragging to its benefit and RSA/CNS' detriment. The foot dragging was acknowledged by Taciuk to Pentland in his email of June 17, 2009 (after the sale to Co-op, but before the announcement and before Pentland has been told of the sale) where he states, when responding to an email from Pentland to Mottram asking Mottram to develop more formalized monthly financial reporting:
<QUOTE><P>I don't think it is fair to ask CNS to do this work until we do have the contract finalized, the delay is clearly our fault. Lai can make the appropriate estimates based on your inputs on commission levels. Once the contract is finalized we will need to do a full reconciliation with CNS...<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR Volume 4, Tab B, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 55, Ex. P.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>79. On approximately May 25, 2009, RSA/CNS was advised by VCU that. VCI had been sold. RSA/CNS immediately wrote VCU and requested confirmation that, among other things, that the &ldquo;Insurance Program Agreement&rdquo; was for a 5 year term with a 2 year cancellation period &ldquo;as the parties agreed&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 109, Ex. 76.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>80. On May 28, 2009, Rob Malli, the V.P. Finance for VCU responded and advised that:
<QUOTE><P>Our view of the relationship between Vancity Insurance Services Ltd. (&ldquo;VISL&rdquo;) and Canadian Northern Shield Insurance Company (&ldquo;CNS&rdquo;) is quite different then than the one you describe...As I am sure you are aware, the form of document for the insurance program that you sent us in early December was CNS' first draft. This draft contained a number of errors, was never signed and does not reflect VISL's understanding of the current business arrangement between VISL and CNS.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 110, Ex. 77.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>There is no evidence that Malli had any meaningful involvement in the Program or that he attended any meetings where the Agreement was discussed or the contractual terms agreed to. There is also no evidence that VCI disagreed with any of the essential terms of the Draft Insurance Program Agreement. If there was any genuine disagreement VCI would have raised those issues, rather than waiting until after VCU had signed the sale agreement with Co-op.</P>
<P>81. RSA/CNS was advised on July 21, 2009 that VCI had been sold to the Co-Op, a direct competitor, when the sale was announced on a newswire.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Para. 114, Exs. 81, 82.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>82. By letters dated September 9, 2009 Federated stopped placing habitational insurance with RSA/CNS effective September 10, 2009 or October 24, 2009 for new business and December 10, 2009 for renewals. In response, Keenan wrote to Federated Agencies and stated &ldquo;This notice of termination is not in conformity with the agreement between Vancity and CNS, which called for an exclusive arrangement and two years notice of termination.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Exs. 83, 84; RMR, Volume 4, Tab C, Mottram Affidavit, Ex. 6.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>SALE OF VCI</TI>
<P>83. By December 2008, VCU had determined that it would explore selling VCI. This process, called &ldquo;Project Jet&rdquo; culminated in the sale of VCI to the defendant The Co-operators Group Limited (&ldquo;Co-Op&rdquo;) in September 2009.</P>
<P>84. Notwithstanding the decision to sell VCI, VCI and VCU were concerned about the effect that the agreement with RSA/CNS would have on the potential sale.</P>
<P>85. In an email date December 17, 2008 from Taciuk to Sielski and other Tacuik stated:
<QUOTE><P>As the roll-over to CNS of our current book of business progresses the potential value of our book or at least the complexity of the deal increases so we should be putting this project onto a very fast track.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 46.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>86. In a Vancity document discussing JET the writer states:
<QUOTE><P>How does the implementation of Program [the agreement with RSA/CNS] affect this sale?</P>
<P>This presents a challenge. The more of our book that rolls to only one company the more challenging the sale. Our book is a big book and currently there is a good balance with 3 markets owning the bulk of the book...The contracts with Sovereign General has been cancelled and we are rolling all of this business to the Vancity Pure Home. The Ing contract has been terminated and January 5, 2009 we will begin rolling over policies with mid February effective dates.</P>
<P>The longer we go into the roll-over, the less flexibility the suitor would have and therefore the lower the value.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Ex. 47.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>87. In mid-March 2009, RSA/CNS was advised that VCU was exploring selling VCI. A broker, working with RSA/CNS, bid to purchase VCI but that bid was unsuccessful. Despite the potential sale, VCI continued, day to day while working on implementation of the Program Agreement, to act as if nothing had changed. We now know that Pentland knew nothing about the sale of VCI until 12 hours before the sale was announced.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Hayes Affidavit, Paras. 99&ndash;109, Exs. 69&ndash;76; RMR, Volume 4, Tab B RMR, Volume 1, Tab A, Pentland Affidavit, Para. 54.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>ABSENCE OF ESSENTIAL TERMS</TI>
<P>88. In their factum VCU and VCI point to a number of terms that they allege were essential and were not finalized by the Parties as evidence that there was no binding agreement. However they provide no evidence that the terms they say were not finalized are essential. Pentland's evidence given at cross-examination when asked about a number of items that were outstanding including KPI's (although he said only contingency profit was outstanding), financial services; (his evidence was that the $5 million deposit was offered by RSA/CNS, and nothing further was expected by CNS); agreement on specific growth targets over the three-year period; specific strategies had not been agreed to to achieve targets, and strategies had not been developed for community leadership, Pentland responded:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>No. And nor would&mdash;nor would there been an expectation that you would have all of this agreed to at any particular time. The primary focus is on the rollover of the business and the amount of work and effort to do that. So your first year&mdash;six months planning and full year is all rollover. So, like, community services and community investment and partnering, even KPIs to a large extent, is really year two once you've got the book on what&mdash;the portfolios on the books, and then you're starting to get more strategic around how are we going to grow it, how are we going to cross-market it, That type of things...you always want to be talking about where you want to take the partnership. It's a new partnership. Where you want to take it, and you want to always be talking about those types of things.</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Cross-examination of Glen Pentland, P. 24, L. 6&ndash;9; P. 25, L. 1&ndash;24; P. 27.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>Pentland's evidence recognizes that some of the detail of the implementation of the Program Agreement could not be decided so early in the process, and this was acceptable to the Parties.</P>
<P>89. The best evidence that there was an agreement between the Parties on the essential terms is the Draft Insurance Program Agreement and the fact that VCI made no material comment disputing any of the essential terms in the Draft Insurance Program Agreement prior to the sale of VCI to Co-op. In addition VCI cancelled the other insurance agreements and rolled over, over 9000 of its customers to RSA/CNS, its exclusive supplier of habitational insurance which would not have happened had there not been an agreement between the Parties on the essential terms governing their relationship.</P>
<P>90. It is improper for VCI/VCU to use its own failure to address the Draft Insurance Program Agreement to support its position that there was no binding agreement.</P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>ISSUES AND THE LAW</TI>
<P>91. This case presents two issues:
<P1>(a) is summary judgment an appropriate mechanism to determine the enforceability of the Program Agreement; and</P1>
<P1>(b) is there a valid agreement between RSA/CNS and VCI.</P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>SUMMARY JUDGMENT</TI>
<P>92. RSA/CNS agree that the issue of whether or not the Program Agrement is enforceable does not require a trial and that it is an appropriate issue to be determined on a motion for summary judgment. The evidence available is sufficient for a fair and just determination of that issue.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hyrniak v Maudlin</SOC></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK3>
<BLOCK3><TI>AGREEMENT</TI>
<P>93. RSA/CNS takes the position that the oral agreement that was arrived at in July and September 2008, the terms of which are not in dispute, constitute a valid, enforceable contract. In other words the terms agreed to orally at the July 3 Meeting and the September 11 Meeting were the essential terms defining the legal relationship between VCI and RSA/CNS. The Ontario Court of Appeal had the following to say about such contracts:
<QUOTE><P>As a matter of normal business practice, parties planning to make a formal written document the expression of their agreement, necessarily discuss and negotiate the proposed terms of the agreement before they enter into it. They frequently agree upon the all of the terms to be incorporated into the the intended written document before it is prepared. Their agreement may be expressed orally or by way of memorandum, by exchange of correspondence, or other informal writings. The parties may &ldquo;contract to make a contract&rdquo;, that is to say, they may bind themselves to execute at a future date a formal written agreement containing specific terms and conditions. <BOLD>When they agree on all of the essential provisions to be incorporated in a formal document with the intention that their agreement shall thereupon become binding, they will have fulfilled all of the requisites for the formation of a contract. The fact that a formal written document to the same effect is to be thereafter prepared and signed does not alter the binding validity of the original contract</BOLD>. [emphasis added]<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Bawitko Investments Ltd. v Kernels Popcorn Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1991 CanLii 2734</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 12.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>94. Further decisions of the Ontario Court of Appeal have confirmed that for a concluded contract to exist a court must find that; a) that the parties had a mutual intention to create a legally binding contract and b) that they reached agreement on all of the essential terms of the agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Olivieri v Sherman</SOC><CITE>2007 ONCA 491 (CanLii)</CITE><PARANUM>41</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>UBS Securities Candan Inc. v Sands Brothers Canada Ltd.</SOC><CITE>95 O.R. (3d) 93</CITE><PARANUM>79</PARANUM></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Erie Sand and Gravel Limited v Tri-B Acres Inc.</SOC><CITE>2009 ONCA 709 (CanLii)</CITE><PARANUM>42&ndash;46</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>95. In <CASEREF><SOC>Ward v Ward</SOC></CASEREF> the Ontario Court of Appeal said:
<QUOTE><P>At common law, an agreement is binding if the parties consider that it contains all essential terms, even if the parties also agree that those terms will subsequently be recorded in a [page 413] more formal document together with the usual terms ancillary to that type of agreement. However, an agreement is not final or binding if it is merely an agreement to later agree on essential provisions or to defer the binding nature of the agreement until the execution of the proposed subsequent formal contract. The proper approach was discussed in <CASEREF><SOC>Bogue v. Bogue</SOC><YEAR>1990</YEAR><CITE>46 O.R. (3d) 1</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1999] O.J. No. 4310</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, where, at para. 12, Rosenberg J.A. cites Robins J.A. in <CASEREF><SOC>Bawitko Investments Ltd. v. Kernels Popcorn Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1991 CanLII 2734</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1991] O.J. No. 495</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>79 D.L.R. (4th) 97</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, at pp. 103-104 D.L.R., as explaining the &ldquo;true legal position...&rdquo; [Quote from Bawitko in para, above]</P>
<P>As well, to be binding, it is not necessary that the original contract include all the ancillary terms that are already implicit in its content. As Rosenberg J.A. observed in Bogue, at para. 13:</P>
<P>While there was no express discussion about a release, the settlement of the action implied an obligation to furnish releases: <CASEREF><SOC>Fieguth v. Acklands Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1989</YEAR><CITE>1989 CanLII 2744</CITE><COURTJUR>BC CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>59 D.L.R. (4th) 114</CITE><COURTJUR>B.C.C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>. At the end of those negotiations, the parties had bound themselves to the settlement. It only remained for the lawyers to reduce the terms to a formal document. This was not simply an agreement to agree.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ward v Ward</SOC><CITE>2011 ONCA 178 (CanLii)</CITE><PARANUM>53-54</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>96. As to how to determine what is essential, The Federal Court of Appeal<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Apotex Inc. v. Allergan Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 FCA 155</CITE><PARANUM>31&ndash;33</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> said the following:
<QUOTE><P>How does a court decide what terms are essential and what terms are not?</P>
<P>The court is to view the specific facts of the case objectively in light of the practical circumstances of the case and ask whether the parties intended to be legally bound by what was already agreed or, in other words, whether an &ldquo;honest, sensible business[person] when objectively considering the parties' conduct would reasonably conclude that the parties intended to be bound or not&rdquo; by the agreed-to terms: <CASEREF><SOC>G Percy Trentham Ltd v Archital Luxfer Ltd</SOC><YEAR>1992</YEAR><CITE>[1993] 1 Lloyd's Rep 25</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>63 B.L.R. 44</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at paras. 50 and 86; <EM>Ward</EM> at para. 61; <CASEREF><SOC>Hughes v. City of Moncton</SOC><CITE>2006 NBCA 83 (CanLII)</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>304 N.B.R. (2d) 92</CITE><PARANUM>6</PARANUM></CORRELAT></CASEREF>. Put another way, looking not through the eyes of lawyers, but through the eyes of reasonable businesspeople stepping into the parties' shoes, was there something essential left to be worked out? See <CASEREF><SOC>Investors Compensation v. West Bromwich Building Society</SOC><CITE>[1998] 1 All E.R. 98</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[1998] 1 W.L.R. 896</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>H.L.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>;<CASEREF> <SOC>Chartbrook v. Persimmon Homes</SOC><CITE>[2009] UKHL 38</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2009] A.C. 1101</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Re Sigma Finance</SOC><CITE>[2009] UKSC 2</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>[2010] 1 All E.R. 571</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>. <BOLD>Another way of putting it is to ask how &ldquo;a reasonable [person], versed in the business, would have understood the exchanges between the parties&rdquo;:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Bear Stearns Bank plc v. Forum Global Equity Ltd.</SOC><CITE>[2007] EWHC 1576</CITE><COURTJUR>Q.B.D. Comm.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 171</P></QUOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>94. In <CASEREF><SOC>Ironside v Smith</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Ironside v. Smith</SOC><CITE>1998, ABCA 366</CITE></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>, the Alberta Court of Appeal indicated:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>&ldquo;It is not the absence of terms which renders a contract unenforceable, but the absence of terms that are so essential that without them the court cannot ascertain the real intentions of the parties:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>First City Investments Ltd. v. Fraser Arms Hotel Ltd. et al.</SOC><YEAR>1979</YEAR><CITE>1979 CanLII 606</CITE><COURTJUR>BC CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>13 B.C.L.R. 107</CITE><PAGENUM>at 116</PAGENUM><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF><BOLD>. For an agreement to be uncertain, an essential term must be missing:</BOLD> <CASEREF><SOC>Murphy v. McSorley</SOC><CITE>1929 CanLII 29</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1929] 4 D.L.R. 247</CITE><PAGENUM>at 250</PAGENUM><COURTJUR>S.C.C.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>97. Essential, however, does not mean all. The lack of agreement on non-essential terms will not stand in the way of finding there was an agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Apotex Inc. v Allargan, Inc. Op. Cit.</SOC></CASEREF>, at para. 33</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> This even extends to economic or other significant terms that have not been finalized where an objective appraisal of the parties words and conduct may lead to the conclusion that they did not intend agreement on such terms to be a pre-condition to a concluded and legally binding agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>RTS Flexible Systems Limited v Molkerei Alois Muller Gmbh</SOC><CITE>2010 UKSC 14</CITE><PARANUM>45</PARANUM></CASEREF>, quoted in Apotex, Ibid, at para. 33</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>98. Mr. Justice Cromwell (as he then was) had the following to say in <CASEREF><SOC>United Gulf Developments v Iskander</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>United Gulf Developments Ltd. v Iskandar</SOC><CITE>2008 NSCA 71</CITE><PARANUM>14</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> (&ldquo;United Gulf&rdquo;);
<QUOTE><P>To have an enforceable contract, there must be agreement between the parties as to all essential terms. To use the language of a leading case, a contract &ldquo;... settles everything that is necessary to be settled and leaves nothing to be settled by agreement between the parties&rdquo;: <CASEREF><SOC>May and Butcher, Ltd. v. The King</SOC><CITE>[1934] 2 K.B. 17</CITE><COURTJUR>H.L.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at p.21. Determining what terms are &ldquo;essential&rdquo; in a particular case is, however, more difficult than stating the principle. The sort of terms that are considered essential varies with the nature of the transaction and the context in which the agreement is made: <CASEREF><SOC>Mitsui &amp; Co. v. Jones Power Co.</SOC><CITE>2000 NSCA 95(CanLII)</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>189 N.S.R. (2d) 1</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para. 64.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>99. Similarly, the Alberta Court of Appeal<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hole v Hole</SOC><CITE>2016 ABCA 34 (CanLii)</CITE><PARANUM>49</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> has held that:
<QUOTE><P>An agreement that is otherwise enforceable does not fail for uncertainty simply because some of the words in it may be vague or difficult to interpret: <CASEREF><SOC>Mitsui &amp; Co (Point Aconi) Ltd v Jones Power Co Ltd</SOC><CITE>2000 NSCA 95 (CanLII) at</CITE><PARANUM>52</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>189 NSR (2d) 1</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>. In determining whether the terms of a contract are sufficiently certain, a court is entitled to consider the surrounding context that is known to all the parties: <CASEREF><SOC>Klemke Mining Corporation v Shell Canada Limited</SOC><CITE>2008 ABCA 257 (Can LII)</CITE><PARANUM>18</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>433 AR 172</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>. Uncertain terms that are not an essential part of the contract will not be fatal to its enforcement; uncertain or meaningless terms that are subsidiary may be severed from the contract: <CASEREF><SOC>Continental Insurance Company v Law Society of Alberta</SOC><CITE>1984 ABCA 261 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>25</PARANUM><CORRELAT><CITE>56 AR 98</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>100. Justice Cromwell in <UNDER>United Gulf</UNDER> also dealt with the issue of whether or not a written agreement is a condition of there being an agreement in the following terms:
<QUOTE><P>Parties may agree that they will execute a future, more formal document. If they have agreed on all of the essential terms and it is their intention that their agreement be binding, there is an enforceable contract; it is not unenforceable simply because it calls for the execution of a further formal document. The question is whether the further documentation is a condition of there being a bargain, or whether it is simply an indication of the manner in which the contract already made will be implemented. Professor Waddams, in <BOLD>The Law of Contracts,</BOLD> 5th ed. (Toronto: Canada Law Book, 2005) puts the question well:</P>
<P>&ldquo;Is execution of the formal contract a step in carrying out an already enforceable agreement, like a conveyance under an agreement to buy land, or is it a prerequisite of any enforceable agreement at all? ... [T]he test must be the reasonableness of the parties' expectations. Has the promisor committed himself to a firm agreement or does he retain an element of discretion whether or not to execute the formal agreement? In the former case there is an enforceable agreement. In the latter there is none.&rdquo; (section 51 page 36,)</P>
<P>[76] This is a matter of the proper construction of the agreement, viewed as a whole and in light of its origins and purposes: Calvan <CASEREF><SOC>Consolidated Oil &amp; Gas Co. Ltd. v. Manning</SOC><CITE>1959 CanLII 56</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1959] S.C.R. 253</CITE><PAGENUM>at 260-61</PAGENUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>; <CASEREF><SOC>Bawitko Investments Ltd. v. Kernels Popcorn Ltd.</SOC><YEAR>1991</YEAR><CITE>1991 CanLII 2734</CITE><COURTJUR>ON CA</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>53 O.A.C. 314</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>79 D.L.R. (4th) 97</CITE></CORRELAT><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF> at 103-04; <CASEREF><SOC>Mitsui &amp; Co. (Point Aconi) Ltd. v. Jones Power Co.</SOC></CASEREF><BOLD>, supra</BOLD> at para. 67.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><UNDER>United Gulf</UNDER> Ibid, para's 75-76.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>101. Similarly, the Ontario Court of Appeal has held that, even though there is no uncertainty about the terms of the agreement, where the parties understand or intend that their legal obligations are to be deferred until a formal legal contract has been approved, the original agreement cannot constitute an enforceable contract.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><UNDER>Bawitko Investments Ltd.</UNDER> Op-cite, p. 13.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> However, where a written agreement was not the &ldquo;condition of the bargain&rdquo;, the oral agreement will stand.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><UNDER>UBS Securities Canada, Inc</UNDER>. Op-Cite, para. 79., <CASEREF><SOC>Apotex Inc. v Allargan, Inc.</SOC></CASEREF>&rsquo; Op-Cite at para 38, to the same effect.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> There is no evidence in this case that a written, signed agreement was a &ldquo;condition of the bargain&rdquo;. In fact all of the evidence is contrary to this position.</P>
<P>102. With respect to intention, the subjective intention of a party is irrelevant; it is whether the objective, reasonable bystander would conclude that there was an agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><UNDER>UBS Securities Canada Inc.</UNDER>, Ibid, para. 88, <CASEREF><SOC>Cole v Cole</SOC><CITE>2011 ONSC 373 (CanLii)</CITE><PARANUM>30&ndash;33</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> Fridman in The Law of Contract in Canada<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Fridman, The Law of Contract, cited in <CASEREF><SOC>Tether v Tether</SOC><CITE>2008 SKCA 126</CITE><PARANUM>55</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> states:
<QUOTE><P>Constantly reiterated in the judgments is the idea that the test of agreement for legal purposes is whether the parties have indicated to the outside world, in the form of the objective reasonable bystander, their intention to contract and the terms of such contract. The law is concerned not with the parties' intentions but with their manifested intentions. It is not what an individual party believed or understood was the meaning of what the other party said or did that is the criterion of agreement; it is whether a reasonable man in the situation of that party would have believed and understood that the other party was consenting to the identical terms....</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>103. In determining whether the parties have come to an agreement on the essential terms the court can look at the subsequent conduct of the parties.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>VanDyke v The Grey Bruce Regional Health Center</SOC><CITE>2002 CanLii 9302</CITE><PARANUM>37</PARANUM><COURTJUR>ONSC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>2010 ONCA 473</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, <CASEREF><SOC>Cole v Cole</SOC></CASEREF>, Op-Cite at para 33, <CASEREF><SOC>Andrews v Lundrigan</SOC><CITE>2009 ONCA 160 (CanLii)</CITE><PARANUM>8</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>104. In <CASEREF><SOC>Fedel v Tan</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Fedel v Tan</SOC><CITE>2010 ONCA 473</CITE><PARANUM>44 and 50</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> when responding to arguments made by Tan that certain items were not agreed to at the time the oral agreement was formed Justice O'Connor stated (at paragraph 44):
<QUOTE><P>I do not accept these arguments. While some of the details that Tan says were missing in the oral agreement may not have been discussed at the time the oral agreement was formed, any such failure did not hinder the two from carrying on the carrageenan business in the following ten years pursuant to the oral agreement.</P>
<P>[50]: In my view it was clearly open to the application judge to find, on the basis of the oral agreement, that Fedel had a contractual right to 40 per cent ownership in the shares of GPI. Any lack of clarity about the terms at the time of the formation of the oral agreement did not interfere with the way the parties were able to perform under the agreement over a lengthy period to time.</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>105. In order to assert that terms for which there was no agreement, there must be evidence that such terms were in fact &ldquo;essential&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>1549858 Ontario Inc. v 1549857 Ontario Inc.</SOC><CITE>2015 ONSC 1913</CITE></CASEREF> (CanLii).</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In this case there is no evidence that any of the terms referred to by the moving parties are essential. There is no evidence that any of the terms that the moving party says were not agreed to by the Parties were, in fact, essential.</P>
<P>106. If this court should determine that a term in the Program Agreement which is not specified, is essential, then the court can imply that term. As stated by Madam Justice RyanFroslie in <CASEREF><SOC>101060873 Saskatchewan Ltd. v Saskatoon Open Door Society Inc</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>101060873 Saskatchewan Ltd. v Saskatoon Open Door Society Inc.</SOC><CITE>2016 SKCA 98</CITE><PARANUM>49</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE>:
<QUOTE><P>[49] The same conclusion can be reached by using the modem approach to implying contractual terms as set out by the Supreme Court of Canada in <EM>M.J.B.</EM>:</P>
<P>... The general principles for finding an implied contractual term were outlined by this Court in <CASEREF><SOC>Canadian Pacific Hotels Ltd. v. Bank of Montreal</SOC><CITE>1987 CanLII 55</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1987] 1 S.C.R. 711</CITE></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>. Le Dain J., for the majority, held that terms may be implied in a contract: (1) based on custom or usage; (2) as the legal incidents of a particular class or kind of contract; or (3) based on the presumed intention of the parties where the implied term must be necessary &ldquo;to give business efficacy to a contract or as otherwise meeting the &lsquo;officious bystander&rsquo; test as a term which the parties would say, if questioned, that they had obviously assumed&rdquo; (p. 775). See also <CASEREF><SOC>Wallace v. United Grain Growers Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1997 CanLII 332</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1997] 3 S.C.R. 701</CITE><PARANUM>137</PARANUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, <EM>per</EM> McLachlin J., and <CASEREF><SOC>Machtinger v. HOJ Industries Ltd.</SOC><CITE>1992 CanLII 102</CITE><COURTJUR>SCC</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEREF><CITE>[1992] 1 S.C.R. 986</CITE><PAGENUM>at p. 1008</PAGENUM></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>, <EM>per</EM> McLachlin J.</P></QUOTE></P></BLOCK3></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">PART IV ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>107. The Respondents therefore seek an Order dismissing the Moving Parties motion for summary judgment, with costs.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED this day 1<SUP>st</SUP> of September, 2016.</P>
