<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="I">PART I&mdash;OVERVIEW</TI>
<P>1. The Co-Operators Group Limited (&ldquo;Co-Op&rdquo;), and its two wholly owned subsidiaries Federated Agencies Limited (&ldquo;Federated&rdquo;) and 7081332 Canada Ltd. (&ldquo;708&rdquo;) (collectively sometimes the &ldquo;Co-op Defendants&rdquo;) bring this motion for summary judgment to dismiss RSA/CNS's claims against them for inducing breach of contract and conspiracy.</P>
<P>2. Pursuant to a written agreement dated July 21, 2009 (the Co-op Agreement&rdquo;), Co-op, through 708, purchased the shares of VCI, owned by VCU.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Supplementary Motion Record of RSA/CNS (&ldquo;SMR&rdquo;), Tab 4, Portion of Co-op Agreement</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>3. Following the purchase, Federated purported to terminate the 1998 Agreement and the 2004 Agreement (sometimes collectively referred to as the &ldquo;Old Agreements&rdquo;).</P>
<P>4. The theme of the defence of the Co-op Defendants is that they did not know that VCI and RSA/CNS had entered in to the Program Agreement and therefore cannot be held liable for inducing breach of contract. This simply ignores the facts. On their own evidence it is clear that they did know, or were willfully blind, to the fact that since July 2008, VCI and RSA/CNS were operating under the Program Agreement, not the Old Agreements and in terminating the Old Agreements, they in fact, terminated the Program Agreement.</P>
<P>5. The Co-Op Defendants also assert the quite frankly ridiculous position that as VCU had already decided to breach the Program Agreement by selling the shares of VCI, nothing the Coop Defendants did caused the breach of the Program Agreement. That position simply ignores the fact that VCU sold the shares and therefore VCI remained liable for the Program Agreement it entered into until the Co-op Defendants terminated the relationship between RSA/CNS and VCI, by purporting to terminate the Old Agreements. Their actions are the direct cause of the termination of RSA/CNS's relationship with VCI.</P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="II">PART II&mdash;FACTS</TI>
<P>6. RSA/CNS rely on the facts set out in its factum in response to VCU and VCI's motion for summary judgment, including the defined terms set out therein.</P>
<P>7. RSA/CNS acknowledges that if this Court finds that if the Program Agreement is not binding it cannot succeed in its claim against the Co-op Defendants or any one of them, for inducing breach of contract. If however the Program Agreement was a valid agreement there is ample evidence to indicate that the Co-op Defendants knew that VCI and RSA/CNS were not operating under the Old Agreements but a new and different agreement with significantly different terms.</P>
<P>8. Early in its due diligence investigations the Co-op Defendants learned that since 2008, VCI had:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>...Established a strategy with CNS (Vancity Pure Home Program) with unique features (environmental coverages) and generous commission rates (23.5%initially and moving to 25%. CNS is also paying a 5% rollover commission and a $135K incremental commission upon contract signing (note: the actual contract is not in the data room).</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>Fraser [VCI] has put the other insurers on notice and is now rolling over business from Sovereign, Aviva, Ing, Axa and Wawanesa to CNS (started in November 2008 and will be staggered and complete in 2010).</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>SMR, Tab 3A</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>9. The terms set out above are significantly different from the Old Agreements, which were non exclusive, paid a commission rate of 20% and did not pay a roll-over commission or pay the $135,000 &ldquo;incremental commission&rdquo;.</P>
<P>10. By April 3, 2009 the Co-Op Defendants were reporting internally that:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>VISL developed a branded program with CNS with a strategy to roll over all business from their other markets to this program. The policy includes $10,000 of &ldquo;environmental cover&rdquo;...The commission terms and roll-over commission are very generous improving their revenue stream in the brokerage. They started in November and added 6 contract staff to manage the roll-over...</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>We asked management how they thought CNS would react if The Co-operators was the successful purchaser and the discussion didn't produce any conclusions. We also discovered that they do not have a current contract with CNS outlining the new terms which should be highlighted as a &ldquo;risk&rdquo; to this transaction.</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>SMR, Tab 3B, p. 2</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>11. The Co-op defendants understood that prior to the &ldquo;branded program&rdquo; there were a number of different insurers providing home insurance to VCI's clients and that as a result of the &ldquo;branded program&rdquo;, and that all of the habitational business from their other markets was moving to RSA/CNS.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Asher CX, Q. 163.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Co-op Defendants also concluded that there was a &ldquo;high risk&rdquo; of a negative reaction from RSA/CNS, if Co-op purchased VCI.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Asher CX, Q. 188, SMR Tab 3D, Risk Assessment (Tab 8, Co-op Answers to Undertakings)</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>12. By June 23, 2009, the Co-op Defendants had been provided by VCI with the Draft Insurance Program Agreement and the 2004 Agreement and been advised that:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>...Michele Buttles [a VCI employee] referred to the CNS &ldquo;draft&rdquo; contract and suggested CNS will hold them to the terms contained in this... and</BOLD></P>
<P><BOLD>...lawyers for Vancity are taking the position that it is the 2004 contract that is in force whereas lawyers for CNS are taking the position that the 2008 draft is in force...</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>SMR, Tab 3C pages 1 and 6, Asher CX Q's 202&ndash;204</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>13. Schedule 5.3 (12) to the Co-op Agreement provides as follows:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>CNS is currently providing insurance services to the Corporation [VCI] on the basis of a relationship without a formal written contract. The terms of this relationship are not easily ascertained, but some of them may be included in a draft agreement provided by CNS to the Corporation in December 2008. The terms of the relationship were never settled. CNS is claiming that the arrangement may contain a 5 year term with a two year termination provision and exclusivity provisions. The Corporation and its legal counsel have received an email dated May 25, 2009 and a letter dated June 25, 2009 setting out CNS's position with respect to this arrangement.</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>SMR, Tab 4, Portion of Co-op Agreement, page 10</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>14. All of the evidence that the Co-op Defendants had prior to entering into the Co-op Agreement indicated that RSA/CNS and VCI were operating under terms that were fundamentally different from the Old Agreements. In the end they simply &ldquo;did not care&rdquo;.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Asher CX, Q &ellip10;</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>15. The Co-op Defendants knew before they entered the agreement with VCU that although there was no signed agreement, RSA/CNS were taking the position that the Program Agreement was enforceable. The Co-op Defendants simply didn't care; all they were concerned about was whether there was a written, signed agreement or, at the end of the day an enforceable agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Asher CX, Q's 88&ndash;90, 132, 231, 236</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>16. In fact Co-op admits that it did not have to form an opinion about which contract was enforceable because it had the indemnity.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Asher CX, Q 236, 257</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>17. The Co-op Defendants knew before closing, that RSA/CNS was insisting on the terms of the Program Agreement including the two year termination provision.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>SMR, Tab 3F</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>18. The Co-op Defendants had a simple solution to the &ldquo;high risk&rdquo; that the terms of the Program Agreement were in force: obtain an indemnity from VCU, which they did as a part of the Co-op Agreement.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>SMR, Tab 3D, Risk Assessment, Asher CX 257, 186&ndash;188, 226&ndash;228, 236</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> The Indemnity provides:
<QUOTE><P><BOLD>In addition to any other indemnifications by Vancity contained in this Agreement and subject to this Article 8, Vancity shall indemnify and save harmless the Corporation [VCI], the Purchaser and the Co-operators Group limited from any and all Losses suffered or incurred by the Corporation, the Purchaser or the Co-operators Group Limited as a result of or arising directly or indirectly our of or in connection with:</BOLD></P>
<P>&ellipsis;</P>
<P><BOLD>(f) subject to the Co-operators complying with its obligations under Section 6.10, any Claim made against the Corporation, the Purchaser or Co-operators Group Limited arising out of the Insurer Agreements with CNS or Royal &amp; Sun Alliance Insurance Company, directly or indirectly as a result of the Transaction;</BOLD><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>SMR Tab 4 page 3-4</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>19. The Co-op Defendants acknowledge that because of the indemnity they simply did not care and it was irrelevant to them whether the Program Agreement was binding.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Asher CX, Q. 257, 308</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> In addition they acknowledge that because they had the indemnity, they did not have to form an opinion as to whether the Program Agreement was enforceable.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Asher CX, Q. 236, 308</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>20. By letters dated September 1, 2009, Federated, purported to terminate the 1998 Broker Agreement and the 2004 Broker Agreement (the &ldquo;Termination Letters&rdquo;). Ken Keenan, the President of CNS wrote to Federated and stated &ldquo;This notice of termination is not in conformity with the agreement between Vancity and CNS, which called for an exclusive arrangement and two years notice of termination.&rdquo;<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>Hayes Affidavit, Ex 83 and 84; Mottram Affidavit, Ex 6</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>21. RSA/CNS continued to write Insurance under the Program Agreement until terminated by Federated.</P>
<P>22. VCI and Co-op agreed in s. 6.10B of the Co-op Agreement that it would attempt to &ldquo;settle&rdquo; RSA/CNS's claims under the Program Agreement by offering to RSA/CNS a portfolio of &ldquo;some substandard auto business&rdquo; in exchange for a Release. RSA/CNS did not agree to this.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>SMR Tab 4 page 2A s.6.10B; CX JA&mdash;Q's 261&ndash;266, 273.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="III">ISSUES AND THE LAW</TI>
<P>23. The issues in this motion are:
<P1>a) Is this an appropriate matter for summary judgment; and</P1>
<P1>b) Did the Co-op Defendants, or one of them, induce VCI to breach the Program Agreement.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="IV">SUMMARY JUDGMENT</TI>
<P>24. RSA/CNS agree that the issue of whether the Co-op Defendants or one of them induced VCI to breach the Program Agreement does not require a trial and that it is an appropriate issue to be determined on a motion for summary judgment. The evidence available is sufficient for a fair and just determination of this issue.
<P1><CASEREF><SOC>Hyrniak v Maudlin</SOC></CASEREF></P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="V">INDUCING BREACH OF CONTRACT</TI>
<P>25. The broad parameters of the tort of inducing breach of contract are well established. In <CASEREF><SOC>Drouillard v Cogeco</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Drouillard v Cogeco Cable Inc.</SOC><CITE>2007 ONCA 322 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>26</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> the Ontario Court of Appeal sets out the four elements as follows:
<P1>a) there must be a valid and enforceable contract;</P1>
<P1>b) the party must be aware of the contract;</P1>
<P1>c) the party must intend to and actually procure a breach of that contract; and</P1>
<P1>d) damage must be suffered.</P1></P>
<P>26. RSA/CNS acknowledges that if this Court finds that the Program Agreement is not a valid and enforceable contract it can not succeed in its action against the Co-op Defendants. However, as set out in its factum in response to VCU's motion for summary judgment, there is overwhelming evidence that the Program Agreement is a valid and enforceable agreement.</P>
<P>27. The Co-op Defendants were certainly aware of the Program Agreement and its significant terms. They were aware that since November 2008, VCI and RSA/CNS were in fact operating under its terms and those terms were significantly different from the Old Agreements. Prior to closing they had reviewed the Draft Program Agreement and had been advised that RSA/CNS was insisting on a two-year termination. The fact that they may not have known the exact terms is irrelevant.<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><UNDER>Drouillard</UNDER>, Ibid, para. 26</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>28. Lord Denning in <CASEREF><SOC>Emerald Construction Co v Lowthian</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Emerald Construction Co. v. Lowthian</SOC></CASEREF> quoted in <CASEREF><SOC>Homelife Realty Services Inc. v. Homelife Performance Realty Inc.</SOC><CITE>2007 CanLII 54275</CITE><COURTJUR>ON SC</COURTJUR></CASEREF> at para 215</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> said the following:
<QUOTE><P>[215] ...that the parties [to a contract] had a right to have their contractual relations preserved inviolate without unlawful interference by others...Even if they did not know of the actual terms of the contract, but had the means of knowledge&mdash;which they deliberately disregarded&mdash;that would be enough. Like the man who turns a blind eye. So here, if the officers deliberately sought to get this contract terminated, heedless of its terms, regardless whether it was terminated by breach or not, they would do wrong. For it is unlawful for a third person to procure a breach of contract knowingly or recklessly, indifferent whether it is a breach of [sic] not. (<UNDER>Emerald Construction Co</UNDER>., quoted in <UNDER>Homelife Reality</UNDER>, followed in <CASEREF><SOC>McKenzie v Peel County</SOC></CASEREF>)</P></QUOTE></P>
<P>29. The Alberta Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>369413 Alberta Ltd. v Pocklington</SOC></CASEREF>,<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>369413 Alberta Ltd. v. Pocklington</SOC><CITE>2000 ABCA 307 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>41, 45</PARANUM></CASEREF>.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE> said the following about the necessary intention:
<QUOTE><P>42 ...Turning a blind eye may include situations in which the defendant failed to seek advice or employ the means available to obtain the necessary knowledge. For example, in <CASEREF><SOC>Royal Bank of Canada v. Wilton</SOC><YEAR>1995</YEAR><CITE>165 A.R. 261</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR></CASEREF>, the defendant was uncertain about the enforceability of a contract, had the &ldquo;means of knowledge&rdquo; to determine if a legitimate contract existed, but made no efforts to seek advice. This court found the defendant liable because he deliberately chose not to acquire the information, but proceeded on the basis that the contract was unenforceable. Similarly, when there are competing legal interpretations and the defendant adopts an interpretation which will interfere with the plaintiffs rights, the defendant &ldquo;must at least show that he was advised and honestly believed that he was legally entitled to take that course&rdquo;: <CASEREF><SOC>Swiss Bank v Lloyds Bank</SOC><CITE>[1979] Ch. 548</CITE><PAGENUM>at 580</PAGENUM><COURTJUR>Ch.D.</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>reversed on other grounds</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>[1982] A.C. 584</CITE><COURTJUR>C.A.</COURTJUR><CASEHIST><CASEDISP>affirmed</CASEDISP><CASEREF><CITE>[1982] A.C. 604</CITE><COURTJUR>H.L.(E.)</COURTJUR></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF></CASEHIST></CASEREF>.</P>
<P>45 ...Therefore, if the breach was a reasonable or foreseeable consequence of that transfer, or alternatively, if Pocklington completed the transfer recklessly, <BOLD>was wilfully blind to [<EM>page 127</EM>] its consequences, or was indifferent as to whether or not it caused a breach, the necessary intent element for the tort will be met.</BOLD></P></QUOTE></P>
<P>30. The effect of the Termination Letters was to terminate the Program Agreement. Because of the indemnity, the Co-op Defendants simply did not care that their actions would breach the Program Agreement. &ldquo;Indifference equals intent&rdquo;. (Drouillard).<FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P>In addition to Emerald Construction, Op Cit., see Drouillard Op Cit, para. 30.</P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE></P>
<P>31. Finally, there is no doubt that RSA/CNS suffered damage as a result of the action by the Co-Op Defendants in breach the Program Agreement. It terminated RSA/CNS's issuing of policies by the latest December 10, 2009.</P>
<P>32. Although to this point the actual damages suffered by RSA/CNS is not an issue on this motion, it is clear that for the purpose of satisfying the requirement of the tort of inducing breach of contract RSA/CNS have suffered damage.</P>
<P>33. As the Ontario Court of Appeal said in <CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton v. Metcalfe</SOC></CASEREF><FOOTNOTE><FREEFORM><P><CASEREF><SOC>Hamilton (City) v. Metcalfe &amp; Mansfield Capital Corporation</SOC><CITE>2012 ONCA 156 (CanLII)</CITE><PARANUM>54-55</PARANUM></CASEREF></P></FREEFORM></FOOTNOTE><UNDER>:</UNDER>
<QUOTE><BLOCK2><TI><EM>Damage and damages are different concepts</EM></TI>
<P>[54] The City's position that damage occurred when the Devonshire notes matured also fails to appreciate the distinction between damage and damages. <EM>Damage</EM> is the loss needed to make out the cause of action. Insofar as it relates to a transaction induced by wrongful conduct, as I have explained, damage is the condition of being worse off than before entering into the transaction. <EM>Damages</EM>, on the other hand, is the monetary measure of the extent of that loss. All that the City had to discover to start the limitation period was <EM>damage</EM>.</P>
<P>[55] The Nova Scotia Court of Appeal in <CASEREF><SOC>Smith v. Union of Icelandic Fish Producers Ltd.</SOC><CITE>2005 NSCA 145 (CanLII)</CITE><CORRELAT><CITE>238 N.S.R. (2d) 145</CITE></CORRELAT></CASEREF>, approved a description of the distinction by A.I. Ogus in <EM>The Law of Damages</EM> (London, Butterworths, 1973), at p. 2:</P>
<P>The terms &ldquo;damage&rdquo; and &ldquo;damages&rdquo; have suffered from loose usage. Some writers and judges have used them as if they were synonymous. But &ldquo;damages&rdquo; should connote the <EM>sum of money payable by way of compensation</EM>..., while the use of &ldquo;damage&rdquo; is best confined to instances where it refers to the <EM>injury inflicted</EM> by the tort or breach of contract...</P></BLOCK2></QUOTE></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI TOCID="VI">PART IV ORDER SOUGHT</TI>
<P>34. RSA/CNS therefore seek an order dismissing the motion for summary judgment, with costs.</P>
<P>ALL OF WHICH IS RESPECTFULLY SUBMITTED this 1<SUP>st</SUP> day of September, 2016.</P>
